<HEADLINE> Maasai Cultural Museum Launched in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A museum reflecting the
culture and the way of life of Kenya's Maasai tribe was launched
Friday in the famous Maasai Mara Natural Reserve in southwestern
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
According to the Maasai tradition, there was no opening speech
for the launching of the museum, which started with the Maasai
custom for slaughtering a cow, and dancing and singing performed
by Maasai young men and women.
</P>
<P>
The Maasai Cultural Museum is about 260 kilometers from the
capital Nairobi. Covering an area of over 1,500 square meters, it
is on a flat ridge among the bushes, completely harmonized with
natural surroundings.
</P>
<P>
The museum consists of four Maasai-style houses built of
branches and cow dung, and two workshops.
</P>
<P>
One of the houses is decked with portraits of all prominent
Maasai elders. Two other houses, the male and female rooms,
contain items used in the daily life of the Maasai men and women.
In another house are displayed Maasai artefacts used for rites of
passage such as animal leather clothes, ceremonial hats made of
fur and feather, wedding necklaces, spears, bows and knives.
</P>
<P>
In the two workshops, one for men and one for women, tourists
can learn how to make the beautiful Maasai items including
jewellery, and how to use such items as spears, bow and arrows.
</P>
<P>
Maasai, one of the major tribes in Kenya, is mainly scattered
in the south and southwest parts bordering Tanzania and the tribe
is still living in nomadic way.
</P>
<P>
John ole Tome told Xinhua that the purpose of building the
museum is to educate Maasai children with the centuries-old rich
Maasai culture, and it will also serve as a bridge between the
Western culture and Maasai traditional culture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
