<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Health Sector Ready to Cope With Emergency Regarding Y2K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's Health Ministry has made
an array of plans to deal with emergency regarding the millennium
problem of its computer systems, an official said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Taisir Sawi, director of the National Data Center for Health and
Population, told the country's Middle East News Agency that the
ministry has adjusted all its computer systems and medical
equipment to ward off the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
An emergency department has been set up in the national center
with three telephone and three satellite lines to deal with any
mishaps, said the official, who supervises the Health Ministry plan
to redress the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
Most older computers, computerized equipment and software
programs were programmed to recognize only the last two digits of a
year. These computers may misread the year 2000 as 1900, causing
technical malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
The millennium problem might affect the computer systems for
electricity, water, payrolls, elevators and gas pumps.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has announced that its government ministries and agencies
and the public sector, including health care, have been secured
against the Y2K bug. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
