<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Human Development Index Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Angola's human development
index for 1999 has reduced to 0.34 points from 0.35 in 1998,
according to a report on the human development in Angola issued by
the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The civilian organizations were considered by the report as the
main force promoting the human development among the population.
</P>
<P>
In many provinces beyond the reach of the government's power,
where the population live in dire need of assistance, especially
in the central provinces, civilian organizations have been playing
prominent roles, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report recommends that the capacity of those organizations
should be reinforced.
</P>
<P>
Angolan Justice Minister Paulo Tchipilica said he hopes that
the society and institutions can collaborate with the government
on the cause of eradicating poverty and creating better conditions
for the future generations.
</P>
<P>
Angola takes the 160th place in a list of 174 countries,
according to another report published by the UNDP in July this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Abstains from Vote on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The Chinese side does not favor such an approach, nor can it
support such a draft resolution. Therefore, we have no choice but
to abstain from the vote," Qin said.
</P>
<P>
China, one of the five permanent members of the Security
Council, believes that in formulating new comprehensive Council
policies towards Iraq, at least three core issues will have to be
addressed.
</P>
<P>
The three core issues include a new inspection commission to
be established to replace the infamous UNSCOM and the new
institution must be "objective, impartial, transparent and
accountable."
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM, established in line with the Security Council
Resolution 687 on April 3, 1991, halted functioning after the
United States and Britain launched air strikes at Iraq last
December. Russia and China have been critical of it for acting
presumptuously without authorization by the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"You may further recall that on such a crucially important
issue as its withdrawal from Iraq, UNSCOM bypassed the Council and
made the decision all on its own. It is our demand as well as firm
belief that the new inspection commission must not repeat the path
of UNSCOM. Its activities must be objective and accountable and
the Council must exercise absolute control and supervision over it,
" said the Chinese ambassador.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the yet-to-be-established new inspection
commission should be sent to Iraq on a true fact-finding mission
and the list of key remaining tasks should be reviewed and
approved by the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador also called on Iraq to undertake to
address these tasks in accordance with approved list and to
accomplish its disarmament obligations as soon as possible so that
the Security Council will lift all sanctions accordingly and in a
timely manner.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Qin also drew worldwide attention to the plight of
the Iraqi people, calling for prompt actions to ease their
humanitarian sufferings.
</P>
<P>
"The nine-year-long sanctions have inflicted untold physical
and psychological sufferings on Iraqi civilians, especially women
and children...the Council, therefore, has every justification to
remove, rather than prolong, the humanitarian sufferings of the
Iraqi people," he said.
</P>
<P>
China maintains that the draft resolution, reinstatement of
disarmament inspections and suspension of sanctions against Iraq
should be linked together. While Iraq is gradually honoring its
disarmament commitment and achieving progress, the Council should
move, timely, to suspend the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"If the new commission reports positively to the Council on
Iraq's cooperation in addressing the key remaining tasks, the
suspension of sanctions can and should be extended automatically,"
Ambassador Qin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Receives Election Materials from Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Canada Friday provided
Ethiopia with election materials worth 2.2 million birr (280,000
U.S. dollars), including 170,000 plastic padlock seals for ballot
boxes.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Ambassador to Ethiopia John Schram and Abebe Mengesha,
deputy chief of the Ethiopian Electoral Board, attended the
presentation ceremony.
</P>
<P>
According to Abebe, the Canadian-made election materials,
which cannot be manufactured in Ethiopia, will be distributed to
some 30,000 election sites throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Canada contributed election materials worth one million birr
(about 140,000 U.S. dollars) during Ethiopia's national elections
in 1995, the Canadian ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia is due to hold national elections on May 14 next year.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
