<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Opposition Party Demands Recounting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the main
opposition party, Mozambican National Resistance (Renamo), Friday
demanded a "manual recount" of all the results from the country's
second general elections held on December 3-5, the Mozambique News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Jose de Castro, a Renamo appointed member of the National
Elections Commission, made the call when the preliminary results
from the 11 provinces indicate a win for the ruling Mozambique
Liberation Front Party (Frelimo) and for incumbent President
Joaquim Chissano.
</P>
<P>
Castro said that his party would put a formal demand before the
election commission for a manual recount "because the computers
are giving us lots of problems."
</P>
<P>
But so far there has been just one proven instance of computer
fraud in the elections. And it was committed by Renamo technical
staff in the northern province of Nampula, who were caught
altering data to reduce the number of Chissano/Frelimo votes.
</P>
<P>
What Castro meant by a recount was to collect all the over
8,300 polling station notices, centralize them, check their
figures, and add them all up.
</P>
<P>
This would be a time-consuming business, and would certainly
postpone any definitive results into the new year.
</P>
<P>
The final results are scheduled to be officially announced
Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
