<HEADLINE> French Court to Judge Nazi Criminal in Absentia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A French court will judge Nazi
criminal Alois Brunner in absentia for crimes against humanity he
committed by deporting 24,000 French Jews to death camps in
Germany and eastern European countries during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse quoted French judicial authorities as
saying on Friday that the case of Brunner, who was described as ``
the engineers of the final solution'' of Adolf Hitler, has been
sent by the Appeal Court of Paris to the Assize Court.
</P>
<P>
Brunner was last seen in Syria years ago and it is not known
whether he is still alive today.
</P>
<P>
Born in 1912 in Austria, he was accused by the French justice
of deporting 24,000 Jews from 1943 to 1944 to death camps when he
was the chief of the Nazi concentration center in Drancy north of
Paris, which was used to temporarily jail Jews destined for death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Switzerland, Germany to Strengthen Cooperation Against Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland and Germany have
pledged to work more closely in fighting organized crime,
according to Swiss Radio International.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement signed Friday in Berlin, Swiss Justice
Minister Ruth Metzler and German interior minister Otto Schily
also agreed to strengthen cross-border police cooperation between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland has signed similar accords with neighboring Austria,
France Italy and Liechtenstein.
</P>
<P>
"The Swiss-German accord is a good example of what can be
achieved if two countries focus their efforts on solving problems
together," Metzler said after talks in the German capital Berlin.
</P>
<P>
The ministers underlined the importance of involving all Alpine
nations to improve the exchange of police information. A working
group is preparing a series of measures which are to be presented
at a ministerial conference in Germany next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
