<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G8 FMs End Meeting in Discord Over Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, December 17 (Xinhua)--Foreign Ministers of the G8
nations Friday ended their two-day meeting in Berlin, passing a
statement on conflict prevention in discord over Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
In their statement, ministers of the seven leading
industrialized nations and Russia said, "UN Charter confers the
primary responsibility for maintenance of international peace and
security upon the Security Council," and "UN Secretary General
also has an important role in this respect."
</P>
<P>
 G8 ministers called for "full adherence to, and when required,
further strengthening of disarmament and arms control agreement,"
saying it was "corner stones of international peace and strategic
stability."
</P>
<P>
They agreed to instruct their political directors to "use
appropriate means...to contribute to the preparation of the range
of conflict prevention issues."
</P>
<P>
Further discussion over the issue will be held at the next G8
Foreign Ministers meeting scheduled for next July in Miyazaki,
Japan
</P>
<P>
The ministers underlined the UN Charter as the first principle
to prevent armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
But not like what they said in the statement, the west again
tried to intervene in Russia's internal affair. German Foreign
Minister Joschka Fischer, who hosted the meeting as G8 chairman ,
said Russia's military operations in Chechnya would hurt its ties
to the west.
</P>
<P>
Fischer, representing his counterparts from the U.S., Britain,
France Italy, Canada and Japan, said Russia should stop its
military actions in Chechnya to "to avoid civilian casualties."
</P>
<P>
He also called on Russia to begin political dialogue with
Chechen authorities.
</P>
<P>
A Northern Caucasus regional conference, including all
neighboring countries and coordinated by outside body such as the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), is "
necessary for regional stability," Fischer said at the final press
briefing after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He hoped Russia to seek a "peaceful, political solution" in
Chechnya and Northern Caucasus after its Duma election on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Fischer used "Chechen war" to depict the situation there,
saying "this war is a serious threaten to the partnership to
Russia."
</P>
<P>
The west interference in Russia's interior policy was rejected
by Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, who had told the
Frankfurt Allgemeine Zeitung newspaper that the west's accusation
on Russia was based on "a shortage of objective information."
</P>
<P>
Ivanov did not take part in the final briefing for "time
constraints, " Fischer explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
