<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Most Swiss Support Closer Ties With EU, UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A majority of the Swiss
population back closer ties with the European Union and membership
of the United Nations, according to the latest survey of national
trends.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at the Federal Institute of Technology in Zurich
was quoted by Swiss Radio International as saying that two thirds
of people asked supported the bilateral accords between
Switzerland and the EU while just over half backed joining the EU.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which focused on national security issues, also
found two thirds wanted Switzerland to join the UN and take part
in its peacekeeping operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Foreign Reserves Stand at 32.9 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 17 (Xinhua) - Thailand's international
reserves stood at 32.9 billion U.S. dollars as of December 9, Bank
of Thailand,the country's central bank, said in a statement Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the central bank statement, the country's net
forward obligation was 3.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that net claims on the government as of
December 9 accounted for 120.4 billion baht (3.12 billion dollars)
while those on financial institutions were 31.5 billion baht (818
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Thailand's foreign reserves were nearly depleted in a failed
baht defense battle against international currency speculators in
May 1997,forcing the then government, headed by former prime
minister Chavalit Yoongchaiyudh, to devalue the baht two months
later, which triggered the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) agreed in August 1997 to
provide Thailand with a 17.2 billion dollar rescue package to help
the Southeast Asian "tiger" fight the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the Chuan Leekpai government, which succeeded the
former one in November 1997, managed to restore the country's
international reserves to about 32 billion dollars in two years'
time.
</P>
<P>
Thailand decided in September this year to suspend withdrawing
the remaining funds from the IMF rescue package after drawing some
14 billion dollars from it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
