<HEADLINE> Britain Demands Explanation Over Japan Nuclear Energy Refusal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 17 (Xinhua) - The British government on Friday
demanded a full explanation from British Nuclear Fuels Limited(
BNFL) on why Japan rejected a controversial shipment of plutonium
from Britain.
</P>
<P>
The demand was made after Japanese nuclear generator Kansai
Electric confirmed that one of its Power Station would not be
using mixed oxides from BNFL, which had already been delivered in
October, after quality assurance irregularities came to light.
</P>
<P>
"I have demanded a full explanation of this clearly
unacceptable failure by management." British Energy Minister Helen
Liddell said in a statement issued by the Department of Trade and
Industry.
</P>
<P>
Liddell also met Hugh Collum, chairman of state-owned BNFL, to
discuss the government's "very grave concerns" about the
falsification of quality control data at BNFL.
</P>
<P>
"I made it clear that steps must be taken to address this
failure and to examine management performance generally. I want to
be assured that will not happen again," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"It is very clear that BNFL quality control processes have gone
badly wrong," said Liddell.  
</P>
