<HEADLINE> British PM Hails "Incredible" Irish Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair on Friday hailed the first meeting of the British-Irish
Council as a historic step in the quest for peace.
</P>
<P>
"We have made incredible progress," Blair said in London after
British and Irish leaders from all parts of the British Isles and
the Irish Republic held the historic first meeting of a joint
council.
</P>
<P>
Blair said his Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, and other
officials from around Britain and Northern Ireland were building a
"partnership for a new age" in the new body, called the British-
Irish Council.
</P>
<P>
The council was agreed under the landmark 1998 Good Friday
accord for a lasting peace in Northern Ireland after 30 years of
violence that has claimed 3,600 lives.
</P>
<P>
But the council also includes representatives of devolved
governments of Scotland and Wales.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Blair told the group gathered at Lancaster House in
central London that they were building a "whole new architecture
of institutional links".
</P>
<P>
"We are setting the seal on a truly unique relationship for the
future, between the Republic of Ireland, Northern Ireland and the
rest of these islands," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
The council, which will meet twice a year, is expected to be
primarily a talking shop, dealing with practical matters such as
the environment, crime, cultural issues, tourism and inter-
parliamentary links.
</P>
<P>
Irish Prime Minister Ahern said Ireland would be able to use
the council to "put forward politics which we might formerly have
pursued with London alone."
</P>
<P>
On Friday afternoon Blair, Ahern, Trimble, and the British
cabinet minister responsible for Northern Ireland, Peter Mandelson,
were holding a separate inter-governmental conference in the prime
minister's Downing Street residence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
