<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek FM on New Spirit in Relations With Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister George
Papandreou said Friday that the new spirit in the relations
between Greece and Turkey had to be given a chance to bloom and
that dwelling on the past was detrimental to both sides.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on infringements of Greek air space by Turkish
fighter jets, Papandreou said that at Helsinki, they saw the
opening of a new dynamic which would allow a new long-term
strategy of improvement in the climate in Greek-Turkish relations.
</P>
<P>
"We did not open the gates to paradise at Helsinki, but we did
open the gate of opportunity," he said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if they dwelt on isolated incidents and on
practices of the past, they would not be able to see the forest
for all the trees.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, formations of Turkish fighter jets reportedly
violated Greed air space over the Aegean Sea and engaged in
simulated dogfights with Greek fighters.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that Turkish fighter activity had been
noted over the Aegean since the European Union (EU) summit at
Helsinki last Friday decided to attribute candidacy status to
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The EU made Turkey a membership candidate at the Helsinki
summit, but set 2004 as a target date for a resolution of disputes
with EU member Greece over territorial rights in the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
For decades, Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have been at
odds over their disputes in the territorial waters, air space
limits and the delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean,
and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Greece now wants the International Court of Justice at the
Hague to arbitrate, but Turkey says it will rather resolve the
Aegean problems through bilateral talks than go to the court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
