<HEADLINE> Ghana to Solve Prison Congestion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 17, (Xinhua) -- Ghanaian President Jerry John
Rawlings said on Friday his government was considering to
introduce parole, suspended jail sentences and community service
to decongest the country's prisons.
</P>
<P>
The issue of congestion at Ghana's prisons, coupled with poor
conditions, has attracted public outcry with human rights
activists calling on government to improve the situation, Ghana
News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
President Rawlings expressed regrets that undue delay in
administration of justice is creating a backlog of prisoners on
remand. This should be adequately addressed by ensuring speedy
trials of cases pending before the courts, he said.
</P>
<P>
In a ceremony welcoming 35 new officers, who are all university
 graduates, into the Ghana Prisons Service, he charged the
uniformed men to treat the inmates humanely, saying though
convicts, they are also entitled to their fundamental human
rights as other citizens.
</P>
<P>
President Rawlings said they were entering the Service at a
particularly difficult moment when the country is facing economic
difficulties due to the drastic fall in prices of export
commodities and the steady rise in imported crude oil prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
