<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany, U.S. Finalize Nazi Slave Labor Compensation Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, December 17 (Xinhua)--Germany and the United States
Friday in Berlin finalized their deal on a 10-billion-mark fund to
compensate millions of slave labor victims in Nazi era, marking an
end to the 18-month negotiation.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough came this week after German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder agreed to raise the contribution of his
government to 5 billion marks from the previous offer of 3 billion.
</P>
<P>
Thus the fund, formally named "the Fund for Rememberance
Reconciliation and the Future", will be composed of two equal 5-
billion-mark parts from the government and the business.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference to announce the agreement,
Schroeder hailed the German-U.S. deal would "provide German firms
with legal protection, secure jobs, and protect German-U.S.
relations
</P>
<P>
The fund is not only to provide material compensation to those
elderly survivors, but also of historical significance, said
Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
"It marks a past century in which the Nazi caused the
holocaust," he said.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that the Nazi dictatorship had forced over 10
million people to work in public and business sectors. Today most
survivors, most over 70, are dying off.
</P>
<P>
Chief German negotiator Otto Graf Lambsdorff said his
government increased its contribution to reflect the state
responsibility for Nazi crimes.
</P>
<P>
"It was the government of the Third Reich that hunted cheap
laborers on the streets of Poland and the Ukraine," Lambsdorff
said, "here we are talking about crimes supported by state."
</P>
<P>
Lambsdorff promised the fund would be set up "as soon and
quickly as possible."
</P>
<P>
Showing U.S. support for the process, American negotiator,
deputy secretary of treasury Stuart Eizenstat announced his
government would possibly contribute 10 million dollars to the
fund.
</P>
<P>
Under the German-U.S. agreement, some 2.3 million Europeans
could benefit from the fund, including about 230,000 slave
laborers who had been forced to work in concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
As an exchange, German firms will get a legal closure that
ensure them immune to further compensation claims by survivors at
the U.S. courts, Eizenstat told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"The German foundation should be regarded as the exclusive
remedy and the dismissal of such cases would be in our foreign
policy interests," stressed Eizenstat.
</P>
<P>
This commitment will be embedded in an Executive Agreement
between two countries and a Statement of Interest to be filed at U.
S. courts, he said.
</P>
<P>
But before the payments can be made, there are still critical
issues to be negotiated in coming months as to how to divide the
compensation among the various classes of victims.
</P>
<P>
Slave laborers in concentration camps will receive more than
the forced laborers, who were deported from their homes to work in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week ,Lambsdorff told Berlin Info Radio that he
planned to pay each former forced laborer 5,000 to 6,000 marks,
and every slave labor victims would get 15,000 marks.
</P>
<P>
To collect the money for the fund, Schroeder is trying to
convince cities and states to contribute. During World War II,
German states and cities deployed slave laborers in public sectors,
too.
</P>
<P>
German industry has also been trying to get more companies to
join the 60 to 70 firms now ready for participation, a spokesman
for German Business Community said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, calling the 5-billion-mark contribution "a
unique effort," pledge for enough time for the firms to collect
the necessary sum.
</P>
<P>
Companies that have committed themselves to participation in
the fund include such big names as DaimlerChrysler, Deutsche Bank,
Siemens and Volkswagen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bomb Detonation Injures 24 in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The detonation of a
car bomb in Colombia's southern Department of Putumayo, injured
Friday at least 24 people, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
The explosive artifact was activated when a military patrol was
passing, and two of its members were injured, said Putumayo Acting
Governor Alvaro Salas in the departmental capital, Mocoa, on the
border with Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
The victims, several of them seriously injured, were taken to
hospitals in La Hormiga and to the neighboring towns of Orito and
Puerto Asis. The car bomb had been parked in front of a luxurious
house.
</P>
<P>
No armed group claimed the perpetration of the explosive attack,
which besides victims, caused damage to houses and commercial
outlets in La Hormiga, some 80 kilometers from the border with
Ecuador. 
</P>
</TEXT>
