<HEADLINE> U.S. EU Pledge to Launch New Round of Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Top leaders from EU and U.S. President Bill Clinton made the
statement after their meeting at the White House, focusing on
regional, trade and other issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides not their disappointment at the failure to reach
agreement on a new round of trade negotiations at Seattle, but
they agree it is now important to find a way forward," they said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"In this context, the EU and the U.S. both pledge continued
readiness to work with (WTO) Director-General Mike Moore and our
partners to launch an inclusive new round as soon as possible,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
EU Commission President Romano Prodi and Martti Ahtisaari, the
president of Finland, who now holds the six-month EU presidency,
attended the summit.
</P>
<P>
Top on the agenda are regional political hot spots, including
Chechnya and Kosovo. The U.S. and Europe have fewer disagreements
in this area.
</P>
<P>
The two sides issued a joint statement, expressing disapproval
of Russia's actions in Chechnya and also a separate statement on
promoting "peace and democracy" in the Balkans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
