<HEADLINE> Saddam Chairs "important" Meeting: INA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
on Saturday chaired an "important meeting" with the attendance of
some senior officials, the Iraqi News Agency INA reported.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting were senior officials including Vice
President Taha Yassin Ramadan and Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz
and Oil Minister Amir Muhammad Rashid, said INA.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here noticed that the meeting was held after
the U.N. Security Council adopted a new comprehensive policy on
Iraq on Friday.
</P>
<P>
China, Russia and France, three of the five permanent members of
the Council and Malaysia, one of the 10 non-permanent members
abstained from voting.
</P>
<P>
The new U.N. resolution stipulates the establishment of a new
arms control body in Iraq and offers Iraq the chance to have the
trade sanctions suspended if it cooperates fully with the arms
inspectors and makes progress on key disarmament tasks to be
defined by the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has repeatedly declared that it will reject any U.N.
resolution that falls short of a total and unconditional lifting of
the nine-year-old sanctions imposed on the country following its
1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
