<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Demands Clarifications From Security Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides on Friday asked for clarifications from the five permanent
members of the United Nations Security Council regarding the
addendum to U.N. Secretary-General's recent report on the
operations of UNFICYP (U.N. Peace-keeping Force in Cyprus).
</P>
<P>
Clerides met Friday morning the ambassadors of the five
countries -- the United States, Britain, France, Russia and China -
- in Nicosia over the addendum, which addressed Turkey's pledge of
support to the breakaway regime in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The addendum said Turkey has voiced its support to the Turkish
Cypriots' position that UNFICYP can operate on both sides of the
island only with the consent of both parties and that the Turkish
Cypriots will request the U.N. force to work with them to "develop
modalities of UNFICYP's operations in northern Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
"Kibris," a Turkish Cypriot newspaper, quoted diplomatic sources
as saying that the addendum is interpreted as an acknowledgement of
the "sovereignty" of the breakaway Turkish Cypriot state.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' Government Spokesman Michalis Papapetrou said the
government's stance on the addendum will be determined after
clarifications are given.
</P>
<P>
"Kibris" reported that the Turkish Cypriot side rejected at
first the Security Council resolution on extending the mandate of
UNFICYP for another six month, a move that led to the addendum.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was passed Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The mandate of UNFICYP needs to be reaffirmed and extended every
six months by the Security Council, usually accompanied by a report
from the U.N. chief on the operation of the force in its current
tenure and an addendum.
</P>
<P>
Such an addendum usually makes reference to the positions of
Greece, Britain and the Cyprus government only.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the addendum is an indirect recognition of the
breakaway Turkish Cypriot regime, Papapetrou said one should wait
for clarifications from the Security Council before making any
interpretations.
</P>
<P>
The five ambassadors promised to look into the matter and return
soon with their answers.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey invaded and
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of short-
lived coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, the Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared the
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," recognized only by
Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The UNFICYP was established in 1964 and the 1,200-strong
peacekeepers are patrolling the 180-kilometer line dividing the two
rival sides.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., EU Puts Joint Pressure on Russia for Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
and leaders from the European Union (EU) Friday issued a joint
statement on Chechnya, increasing their pressure on Russia for its
military operation against rebels in the republic.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued after a summit meeting between Clinton
and President Martti Ahtisaari of Finland, which currently holds
the EU presidency, and European Commission President Romano Prodi.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that Russia's military tactics in Chechnya are
undermining its objectives, creating a humanitarian crisis,
endangering innocent civilians, and jeopardizing stability
throughout the Caucasus region," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"A military solution to the conflict is not possible...the
indiscriminate use of force against civilians is unacceptable,"
the statement added.
</P>
<P>
"We are concerned by the impact of the Chechnya conflict on
security throughout the Caucasus and stress the importance of
avoiding steps that would further undermine the regional security,
" it noted.
</P>
<P>
Russia has rejected the criticism by the Western countries of
its operation against the rebels and terrorists in its republic,
stressing that the issue is a domestic affair and the west has no
rights to interfere.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters following the summit meeting at the White
House, Ahtisaari said, "The concerns that have been expressed at
the summit have been heard in Moscow."
</P>
<P>
"On this issue, we see very much eye to eye. We hope these
developments will not isolate Russia," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and EU leaders also discussed trade issues. In a
separate statement, they pledged to launch a new round of global
trade talks despite the failure to do so in Seattle at the third
ministerial meeting of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
However, they failed to narrow their differences over EU
restrictions on American beef and bananas that pushed the United
States to impose stiff retaliatory tariffs this year on nearly 300
million U.S. dollars in European products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
