<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports Primary Education in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank announced
Friday the approval of a credit amounting to 182.4 million U.S.
dollars to India for the Uttar Pradesh (UP) Third District primary
education project.
</P>
<P>
Complementing other ongoing World Bank-financed primary
education programs in the state, the project will assist UP's
efforts to ensure that all six-11 year old children, especially
the socially disadvantaged, complete a five-year primary education
cycle of appropriate quality, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The project will create about 1.5 million new places by the
construction of approximately 12,300 additional classrooms, 6,050
new and reconstructed schools, and the repair of about 9,000
dilapidated schools.
</P>
<P>
Key innovations under the project include the introduction of
alternative schooling options that will help ensure access to an
additional 180,000 out-of-school children in isolated hamlets and
a model cluster approach for targeted and intensive interventions
for girls' education.
</P>
<P>
Special interventions will also cover working children, school
drop-outs, children with disabilities, and other children from
socially disadvantaged groups.
</P>
<P>
To improve the quality of instruction and enhance learning
achievement levels, the project finances a holistic training
program that provides continuous support for teacher development
and follow-up professional support to teachers, para-teachers, and
alternative schooling instructors.
</P>
<P>
Total project costs are 214.7 million dollars, to which the
Indian government will provide 32.3 million dollars and the
International Development Association (IDA), the World Bank's
concessionary lending affiliate, will provide an interest-free
credit of 182.4 million dollars on standard IDA terms with 35
years to maturity and 10 years grace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
