<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British POWs Angry at Exclusion From Nazi Labor Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Former British prisoners of war
(POW who had been forced into slave labor in Germany during World
War Two, called on Friday for government action after being
excluded from a multi-billion-dollar compensation deal announced
in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
"British POWs have ... been totally ignored in the settlement,"
Martin Day, the lawyer representing the former prisoners, said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The deal is only for civilians and yet many POWs were forced
into slave labor and many were treated totally in contravention of
the Geneva Convention," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"I would still urge the British government to accept its own
moral responsibility to intervene in the negotiations to protect
the interests of British POWs who were forced to work for German
mines and industry in appalling conditions," Day said.
</P>
<P>
Day, who last month went to talks in Bonn in a bid to persuade
negotiators to include British POWs in the compensation package,
said the UK government must "not let the matter drop".
</P>
<P>
Of the estimated 1,000 British soldiers forced into slave labor
by the Nazis during World War two, around 500 are thought to be
still alive.
</P>
<P>
Day said he would on Friday present Britain's foreign office
with further evidence of how Germany breached the Geneva
Convention in respect of British POWs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
