<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-EU Summit Ends in Washington, Trade Disputes Remain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One of the statements issued after the summit said they
continued to be committed to launching a new round of global trade
talks in the aftermath of the failure to do so in Seattle at the
third ministerial meeting of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
EU Commission President Romano Prodi and Martti Ahtisaari, the
president of Finland, who now holds the six-month EU presidency,
attended the summit. The 15-member EU and the U.S. held a summit
semi-annually.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides note their disappointment at the failure to reach
agreement on a new round of trade negotiations at Seattle, but
they agree it is now important to find a way forward," they said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"In this context, the EU and the U.S. both pledge continued
readiness to work with (WTO) Director-General Mike Moore and our
partners to launch an inclusive new round as soon as possible,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed that the new round has to be "definitively
different from its predecessors."
</P>
<P>
"It should encompass the built-in agenda of agriculture and
services, further and effective market access liberalization,
support our efforts to harness globalization by strengthening and
extending WTO rules, and address the concerns of both developing
countries and civil society," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Trade ministers from 135 WTO members failed to launch the new
round in Seattle early this month due to sharp differences between
the developed and the developing countries, and disputes between
the industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and the EU stressed the need to take full account of
the lessons of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
They said work should be directed towards a set of measures
that will provide more participation by the poor countries, offer
great transparency and boost overall public support for the WTO.
</P>
<P>
On labor, the U.S. and the EU agreed that they will work with
other members to "engage the WTO and ILO (The International Labor
Organization) in a constructive dialogue, including consideration
of the relationship between core labor standards, further
liberalization, trade policy and social development."
</P>
<P>
Referring to environment, they said they will work together to
ensure that trade rules support and do not undermine the ability
of governments to establish and achieve high levels of
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
They affirmed their commitment to "maximizing the benefits
developing countries gain from being in the WTO."
</P>
<P>
"We agreed to take forward a preferential market access
initiative for least developed WTO members," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
A separate statement on Chechnya said, "We believe that Russia'
s military tactics in Chechnya are undermining its objectives,
creating a humanitarian crisis, endangering innocent civilians,
and jeopardizing stability throughout the Caucacus region," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"A military solution to the conflict is not possible... the
indiscriminate use of force against civilians is unacceptable,"
the statement added.
</P>
<P>
"We are concerned by the impact of the Chechnya conflict on
security throughout the Caucasus and stress the importance of
avoiding steps that would further undermine the regional security,
" it noted.
</P>
<P>
Russia has rejected the criticism by the Western countries of
its operation against the rebels and terrorists in Chechnya,
stressing that the issue is a domestic affair and the West has no
rights to interfere.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters following the summit meeting at the White
House, Ahtisaari said, "The concerns that have been expressed at
the summit have been heard in Moscow."
</P>
<P>
"On this issue, we see very much eye to eye. We hope these
developments will not isolate Russia," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also issued a joint statement on Southeastern
Europe. "We intend to work closely with Southeastern Europe to
take full advantage of the opportunity before us at the verge of a
new century to forge greater stability and advance the region's
integration into the Euro-Atlantic mainstream."
</P>
<P>
However, they failed to narrow their trade disputes and
differences, including those over EU restrictions on American beef
and bananas that pushed the United States to impose stiff
retaliatory tariffs this year on nearly 300 million U.S. dollars
in European products.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-EU disputes on agriculture was one of the major
reasons for the failure in Seattle to launch a new round of trade
talks. The U.S. asked the EU to remove all its farm subsidies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
