<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Among ALADI Countries Falls Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Exports among the 12 member
countries of the Latin American Integration Association (ALADI)
dropped 25.8 percent in 1999, in comparison with 1998, said Juan
Francisco Rojas Penso, general secretary of the organization.
</P>
<P>
Exports among the ALADI countries diminished from 43.213
billion dollars in 1998 to 32,038 billion dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Among ALADI members, imports also reduced from 45.361 billion
dollars to 34.238 billion dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
However, in the ALADI countries global trade with the rest of
the world, the exports increased from 251.296 billion dollars in
1998 to 255.424 billion dollars in 1999, which means a 1.6 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
ALADI countries imports from the rest of the world diminished 8.
4 percent, dropping from 286.071 billion dollars in 1998 to 262.
173 billion dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Rojas said that the economy of the ALADI countries as a whole
will drop this year about 0.5 percent, the first drop in this last
decade. With the exception of Bolivia, Cuba, Peru, and Mexico, the
rest will have a negative growth.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan economist said that the contraction of the trade
among the ALADI countries also thwarts the process of integration
between the Community of Andean Nations (CAN) and the Southern
Common Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
But he forecast that the economy of the ALADI countries will
improve in the new millennium because of the recovery in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
ALADI is made up of Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, Cuba, Chile,
Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Paraguay, Mexico, Uruguay and Venezuela.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
