<HEADLINE>   India Test Fires Naval Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The naval version of "
Trishul,"India's quick reaction short range surface-to-air and
surface-to-surface missile, was successfully test fired from the
INS Dronacharya in the southern state of Kerala Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
Siva Thanu Pillai, chief controller at the research and
development wing of the Defense Research and Development
Organization (DRDO),declared that "the test firing was 100 percent
successful."
</P>
<P>
The test firing was to test the missile's anti-sea skimmer
capability, he said, adding this was the fourth test firing
campaign of the missile here.
</P>
<P>
According to Pillai, Trishul's army and air force version have
already undergone major trials.
</P>
<P>
More trials would have to be carried out before formally
inducting the missile into the country's defense services, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The quick reaction missile could destroy targets coming from
the air, surface and sea and has a nine-kilometer range, he said.
</P>
