<HEADLINE> France to Launch 14 Ariane Satellite Rockets in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 18 (Xinhua) -- In collaboration with its
European partners in the year 2000, France will conduct about 14
space launches via its Ariane rockets, said the executive officer
of the Arianespace group Jean-Marie Luton Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Our priority is to launch about five "Ariane 5" rockets and
eight or nine "Ariane 4" rockets next year," said Luton in a
interview with BFM radio.
</P>
<P>
On December 10, Arianespace sent its maiden "Ariane 5" rocket
with a scientific satellite weighing 39 tons from the French space
center in Guiana, south America.
</P>
<P>
Luton said that Arianespace's commercial results this year are
not good due to a slow-down in orders from clients and in the
delivery of satellites.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the French telecommunications group Alcatel has
chosen the U.S. Boeing and its space launcher Delta for sending 40
of its 80 satellites in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
Alcatel, which is allied with Boeing, expects to develop a
global telecommunications satellite network called SkyBridge by
2003.
</P>
<P>
Luton said that Arianespace is considering investing in
SkyBridge. 
</P>
