<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak will hold talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat Sunday
evening in the West Bank city of Jericho, Israel Radio reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, the two leaders will discuss the issues
concerning the final-status talks and other interim issues about
Israel's troops redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Under the Sharm El Sheikh peace deal, Israel should have carried
out its second troops withdrawal from the West Bank on November 15
and handed over another 5 percent of the West Bank territories to
the Palestinians, but this has been stalled due to the differences
between the two sides over which areas Israel should transfer.
</P>
<P>
On the parallel track, the final-status talks were locked in
disputes over Israel's settlement expansion in the West Bank,
achieving no progress on essential issues.
</P>
<P>
Barak will also brief Arafat on the outcome of the just-
concluded Israeli-Syrian peace talks in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The talks were held between Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouq Al-Sharaa on Wednesday and Thursday. The unprecedented
highest level talks marked the resumption of peace negotiations
between the two rivals after a 45-month freeze. 
</P>
