<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 People Killed in Somali Fresh Clan Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Serious armed
confrontations erupted during the past three days between the
Sheikhal and Biyomal clans living in the Middle Jubba region of
southern Somalia, killing at least seven and wounding seven
others.
</P>
<P>
According to independent sources, heavily armed infantry
militiamen of the Biyomal clan, equipped with assault rifles and
rocket propelled grenades, Thursday attacked the Sheikhal
clansmen-dominated Homboy village, about 40 kilometers northeast
of Jamameh district.
</P>
<P>
During the fighting, the Biyomal clansmen managed to dislodge
the unprepared Sheikhal clansmen out of the village, killing four
of them and wounding three others.
</P>
<P>
The dislodged people of Sheikhal clan then called for help from
southern Somalia and they were reinforced by two battle wagons and
dozens of heavily armed militiamen who left the towns of Haramkah
and Jamameh for the battle field.
</P>
<P>
Fully prepared, the Sheikhal militiamen launched the attack to
re- capture their lost village of Hamboy on Friday. Three Biyomal
fighters were killed and four others wounded during the exchange
of fire and the Biyomal militiamen were finally driven out of the
village.
</P>
<P>
The reason for this upsurge of fighting is not stated
officially. However, sources close to the Biyomal clan indicate
that their militiamen were angered by the killing of the
well-known Biyomal Clergy man, Sheikh Abdurahman Sheikh Barreh, by
the Sheikhal militiamen a week ago at a checkpoint in Dhay Tubako
village near Jilib district.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Barreh had been the chairman of the Consultative Council
for the Islamic Court and the district commissioner of Jamameh
district.  There is no real peace tentative at the
moment, with high tension remaining in the area of the fighting
between the districts of Jamameh and Jilib.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, Mohamed Ahmed Aw-Ali, spokesman of the Sheikhal
Supreme Committee, has called on both sides to secure an
unconditional cease-fire so as to open the gate for talks between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the people in the region to practice maximum
restraint at this critical moment when the humanitarian situation
is deteriorating following heavy rains and floods that devastated
the farmlands of the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
