<HEADLINE> Russian PM Stresses Role of Security Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 18 (Xinhua) --Russian Prime Minister said here
Saturday Russia's security services will continue to play a major
role in ensuring the country's stability and security.
</P>
<P>
"Bodies of state security have always defended the national
interests of Russia," Putin told a meeting marking the Security
Service Day, which falls on next Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, he said such services must not be separated from the
state and "turned into some monster," the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"For several years, we gave up to an illusion that we have no
enemies and paid a dear price for that," said Putin, who headed
the Federal Security Service (FSB) before becoming prime minister
last August.
</P>
<P>
FSB is the main successor of the Soviet KGB (Committee of State
Security).
</P>
<P>
"Russia has its national interests, and we have to defend them,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
In a message read by Putin, Russian President Boris Yeltsin
greeted participants of the meeting, urging the security services
to "do everything to ensure that Russia enters the 21st century as
a strong power."
</P>
<P>
"Today extremism and international terrorism are challenging
the integrity of our country," Yeltsin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
