<HEADLINE> WB, ADB Offer 4.2 Bln Dollars For Indian Road Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) and the
Asian Development Bank (ADB) have agreed in principle to provide
India with 4.2 billion U.S. dollars in seven years for the
development of its road projects, a top government official said
here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Deepak Dasgupta, Chairman of National Highway Authority of
India(NHAI), told a seminar on infrastructure that the World Bank
would extend 400 million dollars while the ADB offered another 200
million dollars a year for India's ambitious national highway
development projects which will cost a total of nearly 13 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dasgupta said that the multilateral lending agencies had
recently agreed in principle to extend the credit line.
</P>
<P>
He said that the central government had already granted
permission to the NHAI to issue bonds and the borrowing would be
through special purpose vehicles, to be created for the purpose.
</P>
