<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM Spokeswoman on U.N. Security Council Resolution on Iraq Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- China is ready to join the
international community in making unremitting efforts to resolve
the Iraqi issue in a fair way as soon as possible, Foreign
Ministry spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue said here today.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations (U.N.) Security Council on December 17
adopted Resolution 1284 on the Iraqi issue, with 11 voting for,
and four abstentions, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Since December last year, the Iraqi issue has been in a
deadlock and, in order to break the deadlock, China has done a
great deal of work in and outside the Security Council, has always
taken an active part in the Security Council's consultations on
the issue and put forward many constructive propositions, she said.
</P>
<P>
Because Resolution 1284 does not satisfy the reasonable
proposals by China and several other countries in terms of setting
in motion the mechanism for suspending sanctions against Iraq and
other major issues, China, together with such Security Council
members as Russia, France and Malaysia, abstained from voting,
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that China has adopted a consistent and clear-cut
stance on the Iraqi issue, and holds that Iraq should cooperate
with the United Nations, and implement relevant Security Council
resolutions in an all-round and earnest way.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the sovereignty and territorial integrity of
Iraq, which is a sovereign state, should be respected by the
international community, she said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the international community should be fair and
objective in assessing Iraq's implementation of relevant Security
Council resolutions, and accordingly gradually ease and eventually
lift the sanctions against Iraq.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of Chinese Science News (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of major science
stories released by Xinhua in the past week:
</P>
<P>
Chinese Physicist Wins International Prize
</P>
<P>
Min Naiben, an academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (
CAS), has been given the 1999 physics prize by the Academy of
Science for the Third World (TWAS).
</P>
<P>
Min is the first scientist from a Chinese institute of higher
learning to receive the prize. He is now a professor at Nanjing
University, one of most prestigious universities in the country.
</P>
<P>
Min was awarded the prize for his achievements in research into
and the manufacturing of superlattice, a type of material used in
micro-electronic technology and the information industry.
</P>
<P>
 China Builds New-Technology Base in Tianjin
</P>
<P>
China has started building a new-technology base in the
northern port city of Tianjin following approval for the project
after a recent evaluation by experts.
</P>
<P>
The base, covering an area of 87 hectares, will be built
jointly by the Ministry of Science and Technology and the Tianjin-
based companies and universities.
</P>
<P>
The facility will serve as an incubator for new technologies
with the goal of developing new industries.
</P>
<P>
 China Uses "Green" Citric Acid-Extracting Technique
</P>
<P>
A new method for extracting citric acid, by using a technique
called industrial iron chromatography liquid separation, has been
successfully employed in industrial production on a trial basis
for one year in China, and is expected to be widely adopted.
</P>
<P>
The technology was created by a research center of the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences and was patented in late 1994. It was
put into trial use in 1998 at a pharmaceutical plant in Fuyang,
Anhui Province.
</P>
<P>
The environment-friendly technology produces no waste or
pollutants, a common occurrence when the old method of extracting
citric acid is used. The new method can also bring in high
economic returns at low cost.
</P>
<P>
China Launches Its First Environmental Protection Website
</P>
<P>
China launched its first website on local environmental
protection in Shenyang, capital of northeast China's Liaoning
Province.
</P>
<P>
The website, in both Chinese and English, was jointly set up by
the city's administration office on environmental protection, and
the economic information center and environment engineering center
of Northeast China University.
</P>
<P>
The new site, www.syepi.com (English) and: www.syepi.com.cn (
Chinese), will provide Internet users timely data on the city's
environmental protection industry and release the latest
information about new products, research results, high-tech
developments, market management, inter-provincial exchanges, and
international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
 China Creates New Hybrid Wheat
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts have successfully created a hybrid wheat using
plants of different genuses, a breakthrough for China's cell
engineering and breeding research.
</P>
<P>
According to researchers with the Chinese Academy of Sciences,
this is the first such cross-fertilization in the world, which has
attracted the notice of scientists worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The hybrid wheat was created by the combination or blend of
wheat cells with a weed originally growing in Australia, and has
been successfully planted on an experimental basis. More than 3.3
hectares of the new wheat have now been harvested.
</P>
<P>
The high-quality wheat is resistant to salt and thus able to
grow in highly saline soil, making it possible to grow wheat in
saline-alkali land, of which there are large areas in China.
</P>
<P>
 China Developing Technology to Reinforce Police
</P>
<P>
China will arm its police with advanced science and technology
to enhance overall operational capacity, according to a recently
concluded national conference on technology for police.
</P>
<P>
A general plan to set up advanced computer networks involving
information technology, command centers, detective work, security,
and modern traffic control, is now being drafted by the Ministry
of Public Security.
</P>
<P>
China will lead the present police system into the information
age in order to increase its ability to rapidly respond to
emergencies, said Zhu Entao, assistant minister of public security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Police Hunt Serial Killer in Marseilles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 18 (Xinhua) -- French police are conducting a
manhunt in the southern city of Marseilles for a man suspected of
killing at least three young women.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the police department said a search was conducted
Saturday morning in three ghetto areas of Marseilles where a large
Algerian community is located.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-year-old Ahmed Cid Rezala is suspected of killing the
British student Isabel Peake on a night train while traveling from
the French city of Limoges to Paris on October 12. He is also
suspected of having killed a 20-year-old student of sociology in
the northern city of Amiens in late October, and Corinne Caillaux,
a 36-year-old mother, on a night train from Calais to a southern
city in France on Monday this week.
</P>
<P>
The body, assumed to be that of the sociology student who
disappeared on October 29 and whose name was not revealed, was
found Thursday in the basement of a house in a middle class
district of Amiens. An autopsy of her body will be performed on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Police questioned the brother and associates of Cid Rezala in
Marseilles on Saturday. The authorities believe the killer is
hiding in the city because he does not have enough money to leave
town and his pictures are posted in every train station in France.
</P>
<P>
Rezala reportedly enjoys traveling on night trains without
purchasing a ticket. Cid Rezala was seen on the two night trains
where the murders of the two young women took place.
</P>
<P>
He was also seen in Amiens in October with a young woman who
was believed to be the dead woman discovered on Thursday under a
heap of coals.
</P>
<P>
The body of Peake was found thrown along the railway line on
the morning of October 13, while Caillaux, who was traveling with
her five-year-old son, was found dead in a sleeping car restroom
Monday night. She was reportedly stabbed 12 times with a knife.
</P>
<P>
A French citizen of Algerian origin with a face described as
menacing, Cid Rezala, was released from jail in May after serving
a prison sentence for rape with violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
