<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of Chinese Science News (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese Navy has made full use of science and technology in
the improvement of its combat effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Navy has emphasized the role of science
and technology in military drills and renovation.
</P>
<P>
Researchers Make Breakthrough in Extracting Hydrogen
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists have developed a new method for making
hydrogen from sea water, but much more money is still required to
promote the application.
</P>
<P>
A research team in Anshan, a city in northeast China's Liaoning
province, claimed that they have invented equipment, which can
produce hydrogen with lower electricity use.
</P>
<P>
They said the equipment uses only 0.93 kilowatts/hour to make
one cubic meter of hydrogen gas -- believed to be the lowest
figure in the world.
</P>
<P>
China to Promote CAD, CIMS Use
</P>
<P>
The State Economic and Trade Commission, the Ministry of
Information Industry and the Ministry of Science and Technology
are drafting measures to push ahead application of information
technology in large and medium-sized State-owned enterprises (SOEs)
.
</P>
<P>
Xu Guanhua, Vice-Minister of Science and Technology, said that
the use of computer aided design (CAD) and computer integrated
manufacturing systems (CIMS) in State-owned enterprises of pillar
industries will improve their technological innovation capacity
and market competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
China Publishes National Nature Atlas
</P>
<P>
The China Map Publishing House has published the Chinese and
English editions of the Chinese National Atlas of Nature compiled
by the Geology Institute of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The atlas, which include 540 maps on the environment, resources,
natural disasters, and the utilization and protection of nature in
China, is a large and comprehensive national atlas, said Chen Yiyu,
vice-president of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Scientists Recommend 93 Popular Science Books
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts and scholars have recommended 93 superior
Chinese and foreign popular science books to the public in a move
to spread scientific thinking and knowledge among the people.
</P>
<P>
The books include 52 foreign and 42 Chinese works and were
chosen by a committee as the "best popular science books of the
20th century," a project sponsored by the Chinese Academy of
Sciences (CAS), the Ministry of Science and Technology, and the
Chinese Association for Science and Technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
