<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French City to Install Video Surveillance Cameras </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The French city of Strasbourg
will install video surveillance cameras in all public places,
including buses, trams and schools, because of rampant violence by
the city's teenage residents.
</P>
<P>
A local budget committee voted Friday that the city will spend
12 million francs (2.1 million U.S. dollars) in two years to
develop a network of surveillance cameras in public transport
facilities.
</P>
<P>
City officials say they have found that once video cameras are
installed on buses and trams, the number of acts of vandalism,
sabotage and attack by delinquents against bus drivers drops.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Mayor of Strasbourg Roland Ries said some of the
budget will be spent on installing video cameras in other public
places, such as schools.
</P>
<P>
He said the local delinquents are shifting their field of
activities from buses and trams to schools because the latter do
not have surveillance equipment.
</P>
<P>
Strasbourg's police force is on the alert as the Christmas-New
Year season is the high time for troublemakers to burn cars and
break shop windows.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 cars were torched by delinquents in the city's
suburbs over the past few weeks, said the police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
