<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Rejects New U.N. Resolution on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraq announced on Saturday it
rejected the new U.N. Security Council resolution on Iraq, the
Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz said in a statement
that "Iraq's position regarding the deliberations held by the
Security Council after the U.S.-British aggression in December 1998
is declared and known and Iraq adheres to this stand."
</P>
<P>
"Apart from predictions and threats resulted from our position,
Iraq is fully adhering to its principled and legal stance and it is
ready to bear all consequences in defence of its sovereignty and
legitimate rights," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has repeatedly declared it will reject any U.N.
resolution that falls short of total and conditional lifting of the
U.N. sanctions imposed on the country following its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Aziz reiterated that Iraq had implemented all its commitments to
the U.N. resolutions in eight and a half years and it was now time
to implement the U.N. resolution 687 for the lifting of the embargo
completely and without any additional restrictions or conditions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council on Friday adopted a new resolution on
Iraq with 11 votes for and four abstentions. China, Russia, France
and Malaysia abstained from voting.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said the resolution issued Friday "does not meet Iraq's
legitimate demand of lifting the embargo... It has come completely
void of any indication to the aggression Iraq has been exposed
to...through the so-called no-fly-zones imposed by America and
Britain alone."
</P>
<P>
The new resolution sets up a new arms control body, named the U.
N. Monitoring, Verification and Inspection Commission (UNMOVIC) to
replace the old U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) charged with
eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
It also offered Iraq a chance to have the trade sanctions
suspended if it cooperates fully with arms inspectors and makes
progress on key disarmament tasks to be defined by the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
"The real objective of America and Britain behind this
resolution is not the lifting of embargo but it is a process of
cheating world public opinion because the resolution... has a long
and complicated string of vague and new conditions which could bear
various explanations in a manner making this bad resolution not
imply an ensurance that the suspension will take place," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
He also complained that the timings in the new U.N. resolution "
are so long in an artificial and exaggerated way."
</P>
<P>
Aziz added that such measures were meant to cope with the
internal situation in America in the year of elections, and the
intentions of America and Britain have come up to surface with the
continuation of their military aggressions in the illegitimate no-
fly zones in northern and southern Iraq and in addition to
America's interference in the internal affairs of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The new resolution "is in form and essence rewriting resolution
687 in an illegal way, a matter that means the Security Council
does not keep its resolutions and does not honor its
commitments..." he said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that some permanent member states (of the Council) that
adopted a balanced stand along several months of debates, would
work for preventing the issuance of this resolution by using
'veto', but we highly appreciate their stand by abstaining to
vote," said Aziz,referring to Russia, China and France.
</P>
<P>
Aziz deplored the stand of Bahrain, the only Arab member in the
Security Council, by saying that Bahrain during two years of its
membership in the Council does not reflect the stand of the
majority of Arab countries and Arab public opinion, but it behaved
like a tail and satellite to the American-British policy.
</P>
<P>
He also castigated Brazil and Nambia by saying that these two
states were firstly adopting stands of a great deal of balance, but
they succumbed to American pressure and blackmail and joined those
who support the ill-fated resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
