<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wiberg Comes Back to Win World Cup Women's Downhill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Former World Cup champion
Pernilla Wiberg of Sweden captured her first women's World Cup
downhill in more than two years here Saturday, holding off
Austrian Renate Gotschl and Hilde Gerg of Germany in St Moritz of
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old from Borlange overcame a knee injury and
finished the shortened Corviglia course in one minute 12.57
seconds.
</P>
<P>
Gotschl finished second with 1:12.79 and Gerg trailed third
with a clocking of 1:12.88.
</P>
<P>
The course was shortened by several hundred meters shortly
before the race due to high winds and seven of the first 13
starters failed to complete their runs.
</P>
<P>
The Swede took her last downhill win in Vail, Colorado, in
spring, 1997. She won the overall season crown in 1997, but has
had a career plagued by injuries.
</P>
<P>
The St. Moritz competition concludes with a super-giant on
Sunday before the women's holiday break. 
</P>
</TEXT>
