<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO to Resume Talks on New Round of Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Members of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) have agreed to resume talks in mid-January on
the thorny issues blocking the launch of a new round of
multilateral trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
At their first meeting here since the failed ministerial
conference in Seattle on November 30 to December 3, the WTO
members agreed to admit Jordan as the organization's 136th member,
said WTO spokesman Keith Rockwell.
</P>
<P>
They approved a WTO budget for the year 2000 amounting to 127.7
million Swiss francs (about 80 million U.S. dollars), a 4.5
percent rise compared to this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
With the developing countries preoccupied with concerns that
the 1995 WTO agreements, including a key pact on protection of
intellectual property rights, must be implemented by January 1,
the developed countries pledged not to challenge them with
disputes in the near future, Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
In Seattle, ministers from the WTO failed to launch a new round
of trade talks. Negotiators were unable to break a deadlock over
politically-sensitive agriculture and labor issues.
</P>
<P>
"There was agreement that...what (has) to do with the Seattle
process, should be taken up in the New Year," Rockwell told
reporters. "They will hold consultations on the Seattle process,
including the issue of deadlines raised by Pakistan and other
delegations." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
