<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Ning and Deng Yaping Voted as China's Stars of the Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, China, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Former Olympic and
world champions Li Ning and Deng Yaping have been voted the China'
s Stars of the Century by the China Olympic Committee (COC) here
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Gymnast Li Ning and table-tennis player Deng Yaping topped
other four nominees of their own genders respectively in a poll of
journalists from the China Sports Journalists Association.
</P>
<P>
Sailboard Olympic gold medalist Li Lishan from Hong Kong, China
won the special bonus of the Stars of the Century with each of the
three athletes receiving a over-one-kilogram-weight gold trophy.
</P>
<P>
Li Ning, who was hailed as the Gymnastic Prince, is the only
Chinese who was voted as oen of the 25 Athletes of the Century by
the International Sports Journalists Association.
</P>
<P>
The gymnast of Zhuang nationality swept six gold medals by
winning the horizontal bar, floor exercise, pommel horse, vault,
rings and the all-around titles at the World Cup in 1982 in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He became the first Chinese winning a trio of golds in the
Olympic Games when he triumphed in floor exercise, vaulting horse
and the rings in the 1984 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Deng Yaping, who was the world number one women table-tennis
player during the span from 1993 to 1998, was the first player who
swept the women's singles titles in the World Cup, World
Championships and the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
She won four Olympic table-tennis golds, the most for a Chinese
Olympian, 11 titles in the World Championships and three World Cup
championships in the 90's.
</P>
<P>
Li Lishan was the only Olympic gold medalist from Hong Kong,
China after she took the victory in the 1996 Atlanta Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Other four men nominees are Rong Guotuan, who won the first
world table-tennis title for China at the World Championships in
1959, Xu Haifeng, the first Chinese Olympic gold medalist who won
the men's free-style pistol in 1984, Chen Jingkai, the first
Chinese who broke a world record when he set a 133kg new world
record in the 59kg category clean and jerk in 1956, and Zhu
Jianhua, who set a world record of 2.39 meters in high jump in
1984.
</P>
<P>
The four women's nominees are Lang Ping, main character of the
squad of the Chinese women's volleyball team which won the World
Cup, World Championships and the Olympic Games in 80's and former
head coach of the national women team, Li Lingwei, former world
badminton champion, Fu Mingxian, former world diving champion, and
Wang Junxia, marathon runner who held the women's 5,000-meter and
10,000-meter world records. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
