<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic news
in brief from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Jeddah Holding Company for Investment was set up
to deal with financing real estate, housing and tourist projects in
Jeddah.
</P>
<P>
The company, with an authorized capital of one billion riyals
(266.7 million U.S. dollars) and a paid capital of 500 million
riyals (133.3 million dollars), will carry out investment
activities with a view to promote economic growth and create more
jobs for Saudi young people, local reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT -- Twenty-eight firms are going to participate in the "
Pur La Femme" fair to be held in Kuwait next January.
</P>
<P>
The event will feature world-famous costumes, jewellery,
watches, perfumes, leather ware, glasses, linen and household
furniture.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to attract 30,000 visitors,local press reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syria received its sixth and last Airbus A-320 plane
under a contract signed with the European plane manufacturer in
1997. The Syrian passenger fleet included 8 Boeings and 7
Tobolevs besides the six Airbus jumbo jets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Airbus said it received 2,200 purchase orders for the
type A-320 and half of the orders had been met. A-320 is used by
120 international airlines, local dailies reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's trade office in Moscow asked Egyptian exporters
to increase their exports of leather ware to Russian markets and
attend regularly trade fairs in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's exports of textiles and leather ware to Russia nose
dived from 491,500 U.S. dollars in 1995 to 36,500 dollars in 1998,
according to figures from Russia's customs committee.
</P>
<P>
The slump was attributed to the financial crisis that hit Russia
in recent years and affected its imports from all over the world
and the shutdown of an Egyptian exporting company namely Hafez &AMP;
Odah that deals with exports to Russia for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Chamber of Leather Industry took part in the 2nd
International Trade Fair in Moscow on March 30 to April 2, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Russia is a huge consuming market for different commodities
especially leather ware and textiles, the office added.
</P>
<P>
The main exporters of such products to Russia are China, Italy,
Turkey, Ukraine and Germany, the Al-Alam Al-Youm daily quoted the
office as saying.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A total of 66 water and infrastructure projects will be
launched in Egypt's Dameitta at a cost of 1 billion Egyptian pounds
(289.9 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The projects, to be completed later the year 2000, will raise
the number of development-related projects to 86, according to a
report by the Ministry of Housing, Construction and New
Communities.
</P>
<P>
Latest technologies will be applied to carry out water and
sanitary projects nationwide, the Al-Alam Al-Youm daily on Saturday
quoted the report as saying .
</P>
<P>
As part of the industrial and agricultural development projects,
five water and sanitary drainage stations will be built in
Dakahlia, Qalyobia, Sharqia and Ismailia governorates.
</P>
<P>
The report stressed the necessity of restructuring the water and
sanitary drainage stations nationwide and opening the door for the
private sector to enhance performance and service in this vital
area. The restructuring process will have nothing to do with the
consumption tariff or price rises, it noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
