<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Imposes 10 Percent Surtax on Imported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia has introduced a
surtax of 10 percent on consumer imports since December 14 this
year, the country's customs officials said at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The new tax is imposed on all consumer goods except
fertilizers, fuel, public transport vehicles and their spare
parts.
</P>
<P>
According to the officials, the duty has been put in place
temporarily and will not be retroactive.
</P>
<P>
All investment items, like capital goods, will be dealt with by
 Ethiopia's Investment Authority, they said.
</P>
<P>
However, this latest regulation has reportedly met criticism
from local importers.
</P>
<P>
The Monitor newspaper Saturday quoted an unidentified
businessman, who has been in the import business for more than two
decades, as saying that the new surtax is prohibitive and will
make the already difficult business impossible.
</P>
<P>
According to the importer, the past two years have been very
difficult for Ethiopian importers who have very little profit
margins left after all the import duties and taxes have been paid.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
