<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Russia Braces for Parliamentary Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Russian voters were given a
final day Saturday to ponder their choices before going to the
polls Sunday to elect the next State Duma, or lower house of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
About 3,550 candidates from 26 political parties and blocs will
vie for half of the 450 seats on the federal ticket, while another
2,300 candidates will compete for the other half in local
electoral districts.
</P>
<P>
As required by law, campaigning for the elections ended as the
final seconds of Friday ticked away. Russians had 32 hours of
relative quiet to think over the choices they will make before
they cast their ballots from 08:00 to 20:00 local time Sunday.
</P>
<P>
What makes the vote more important is that its results will
have a decisive impact on the presidential race next June.
</P>
<P>
"These elections are a launch pad for storming the presidential
heights," said Leonid Sedov, an analyst with the All-Russia Center
for Public Opinion Research.
</P>
<P>
The results of the Sunday vote will give most of the contenders
an indication of where they stand, especially for the two leaders
of the Fatherland-All Russia bloc, former Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov and Moscow Mayor Yury Luzhkov, who are considered anti-
Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Primakov on Friday announced he would run for president, while
Luzhkov has said he might put aside his ambitions in favor of bloc
partner Primakov.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, if the pro-Kremlin Unity party does well, it will be
another plus for Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, whose ratings have
soared amid the military campaign against rebels in the breakaway
republic of Chechnya. Putin has already announced his plan to join
the presidential elections next year.
</P>
<P>
The offensive was launched in September following armed
incursions by Chechen rebels into neighboring Daghestan and a
series of terrorist bombings -- also blamed on the Chechen
militants -- that killed over 300 people in Moscow and two other
Russian cities.
</P>
<P>
In a televised address to the nation late Friday, Prime
Minister Putin urged the Russians to make their voting decisions
carefully.
</P>
<P>
"Come to polling stations and vote, but vote for those in whom
you're firmly sure, those whom you really trust. I know it's not
easy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Although Putin mentioned no names of candidates or parties, he
has already said he is voting for Unity.
</P>
<P>
Besides Fatherland-All Russia and Unity, the other blocs
expected to clear the 5 percent hurdle to enter the new Duma are
the Communist Party and the liberal Yabloko party.
</P>
<P>
While Our Home is Russia, the Union of the Right Forces and a
bloc lead by ultra- nationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky may make the
5 percent barrier for automatic representation, other minor
political groups stand little chance of a seat in the Duma.
</P>
<P>
As the world's largest country in geographic size, Russia
covers 11 time zones. Therefore, voters in the easternmost regions
of Chukot and Kamchatka would go to the polls at 23:00 Saturday
Moscow time, while those living in the westernmost Kaliningrad are
required to end their voting before 23:00 Moscow time Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the balloting started as early as December 4 in some
of the more remote regions.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary results of the elections will be known early Monday
morning, but the final tally will not be published until about 10
days later.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear how many of the 107 million eligible voters
will actually go to the polls. Under Russian Election Law, a 25
percent turnout would ensure the vote's validity.
</P>
<P>
Russian citizens abroad, numbering 850,000, will cast their
votes in 356 polling stations overseas.
</P>
<P>
To ensure security, all Interior Ministry personnel, plus 10,
000 servicemen and 22,000 cadets under the ministry, will be on
duty Sunday. In Moscow, reserve polling stations have been set up
in preparation for any terrorist threats.
</P>
<P>
In addition, over 1,000 observers from foreign countries and
international organizations will be monitoring the balloting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Malaysia For Lifting of Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has urged the
United Nations Security Council to work out a clear sanctions-
lifting plan that would allow Iraq to resume normal economic
relations with the international community.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian permanent representative to the UN Hasmy Agam was
quoted Saturday byBernama news agency as speaking at the UN
Security Council that his country is unable to support the UN's
Iraq Omnibus Resolution as it does not establish a definite
benchmark or a timeframe for the final lifting of the sanctions on
the Gulf country.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia feels a timeframe for the final lifting of the
sanctions ought to be as much the objective of the entire exercise
as it was for an accounting and disposing of Iraq's alleged
remaining weapons of mass destruction, Hasmy Agam stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The indefinite continuation of the sanctions violates the very
spirit and purposes of the United Nations, enshrined in its
charter... These lofty ideals ring hollow indeed in the context of
the reality of the situation in Iraq," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hasmy Agam said that nine years of punitive sanctions was far
too long for any country to bear and that the UN Security Council
had the responsibility to assess the enormity of the effects of
the sanctions on the Iraqi people and must begin the process of
dismantling them as soon as possible on Iraq's compliance with all
relevant resolutions of the Council.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions have had debilitating effects on the Iraqi
population as a whole, especially the elderly, infirm and children
who were deprived of many of the most basic amenities which were
taken for granted elsewhere, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
