<HEADLINE> Australian Sports Chief to Expose Drug Offenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Australian sports chief
insisted to expose any drug cheats at next year's Sydney Olympics,
no matter the International Olympic Committee (IOC) likes it or
not, according Syndey-based Sunday-Telegraph on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Jackie Kelly, the federal sports minister, told the newspaper
that she would identify any drug offenders even if the IOC would
refuse.
</P>
<P>
Under the IOC's existing regulations, only the IOC's Medical
Commission is informed of any positive tests.
</P>
<P>
But Kelly said cheats should be identified to the public as
soon as the result was known.
</P>
<P>
"If I hear there's a positive I'll be chasing it down every
burrow I can because it means some athlete has walked off with
someone else's medal and that's not on," Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
"It would be a shame if, subsequent to the Games, there were
allegations about the way it was done -- about test results
according to the IOC code. 
</P>
