<HEADLINE> Sydney Games Venues Completed Within 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- All main venues for the 2000
Olympic Games around Homebush Bay have been completed by the end
of 1999, according to the Olympic Coordination Authority (OCA) in
Sydney on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This opening of the Tennis Center in December finalized the New
South Wales Government's five-year venue construction program at
Homebush Bay, 16 kilometers west of the city, OCA director general
David Richmond said.
</P>
<P>
Richmond said that no other Olympic host city had finished the
permanent sporting facilities some ninth months earlier before the
Opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic venues that have been built and are operational
include.
</P>
<P>
Following are the main venues and the sports they are going to
host:
</P>
<P>
A. Sydney Showground and exhibition complex - host to baseball,
badminton, rhythmic gymnastics, handball, fencing, judo, modern
pentathlon and the main press center.
</P>
<P>
B. Sydney International Archery Park.
</P>
<P>
C. State Hockey Center.
</P>
<P>
D. Sydney Aquatic Center - host to swimming, diving, water polo
and synchronised swimming.
</P>
<P>
E. Olympic stadium - host to opening and closing ceremonies and
the track and field program.
</P>
<P>
F. Sydney Superdome - host to basketball and artistic gymnastic
finals.
</P>
<P>
G. NSW Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
H. Olympic Park Railway Station.
</P>
<P>
I. Homebush Bay Wharf.
</P>
<P>
Richmond said work was proceeding on schedule on the other
major Homebush Bay projects, including the athletes' village,
international broadcast center, a hotel complex and Millennium
Parklands.
</P>
<P>
Expenditure of the Homebush Bay site has been 2.7 billion
Australian dollars (1.7 billion US dollars), which includes
private sector funded works, the OCA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
