<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi University Confers Doctorates Upon PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Dhaka University, the most
prestigious university in Bangladesh, conferred honorary
doctorates on Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina and Nobel laureate
Professor Amartya Sen on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
An honorary Doctor of Law degree was conferred on Hasina and an
honorary doctorate of science was granted to Sen, at the
university's 40th convocation, also the first since the country's
independence in 1971.
</P>
<P>
Hasina, 52, graduated from the university with a bachelor's
degree in literature in 1973, while Sen, an economist, was awarded
the Nobel Prize in Economics last year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the convocation, the prime minister said law is the
basic structure of the state through which overall management of
the society will be conducted properly.
</P>
<P>
Law will be protected and applied for the interest of the
people through judiciary and executive and everybody has the right
to get the shelter of law, she said.
</P>
<P>
She called for concerted national efforts to establish rule of
law in the society and attain economic emancipation for the
teeming millions of the country. " As a disciplined nation we have
to build ourselves and move forward the trend of smooth democratic
culture and liberal humanity," she said.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival here on Friday, Sen said although he was born
in India, his forefathers were sons of this soil and some of them
had tutored in Dhaka University.
</P>
<P>
Sen had announced that he would donate part of the prize money
for the welfare of the underprivileged in India and in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
University teachers belonging to the pro-BNP White Panel were
reportedly opposed to the conferment of the honorary degree on the
prime minister, arguing that the special honorary degrees were
reserved for scientists, poets, writers and people of outstanding
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Jatiyatabadi Chhatra Dal (JCD), the student wing
of the major opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party, staged an
six-hour hartal (strike) Saturday morning to protest the
conferring of honorary degree on the prime minister. The shutdown
was supported by the four-party opposition alliance.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 pro-strike activists, including the JCD president
and general secretary, were arrested on Friday from their
processions, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
