<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada Says Philippines Ready for Y2K Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said here Saturday that his administration has made all
the necessary preparations to counter the possible effects of the
Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
In a radio-TV program here, Estrada said that he has received
assurances from all government agencies and critical areas in the
private sector that they are ready for the Y2K bug, a built-in
flaw in older computer systems that would prevent them from
reading dates from January 1, 2000 onward.
</P>
<P>
"From what I see there is nothing to fear. I have consulted
many times with Secretary Filemon Uriarte of the Department of
Science and Technology and National Security Adviser Alexander
Aguirre. Both officials are keeping tabs on Y2K compliance," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Uriarte chairs the Presidential Commission on Year 2000
Compliance (Y2K Commission), while Aguirre heads the government's
Y2K contingency task force.
</P>
<P>
In the same program, Uriarte said that the government has set
up Offices of Primary Responsibility (OPRs) in the seven mission-
critical sectors identified by the government.
</P>
<P>
These mission-critical sectors are finance, manufacturing,
utilities, telecommunication, transportation, government services,
and health care.
</P>
<P>
He also said the government has set up an action center staffed
by technical people from all OPRs. The action center, which
started operations three days ago, will be on 24 -hour alert from
December 28 to January 3, 2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
The action center can alert the National Disaster Coordinating
Council (NDCC) in case any emergency is brought to its attention,
Uriarte added.
</P>
<P>
In the energy sector, Uriarte said, simulation tests have also
been conducted on computer systems in power plants, and that there
were no problems detected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT Iraq Rejects New U.N. Resolution on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraq announced on Saturday it
rejected the new U.N. Security Council resolution on Iraq, the
Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz said in a statement that
Iraq's position "is declared and known and Iraq adheres to this
stand."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council adopted a new comprehensive policy on Iraq
Friday with 11 votes for and four abstentions. China, Russia and
France, three of the five permanent members of the Council and
Malaysia, one of the 10 non-permanent members, abstained from
voting.
</P>
<P>
The new U.N. resolution stipulates the establishment of a new
arms control body -- the U.N. Monitoring, Verification and
Inspection Commission (UNMOVIC) -- in Iraq, and offers Iraq the
chance to have the trade sanctions suspended if it cooperates fully
with the arms inspectors and makes progress on key disarmament
tasks to be defined by the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has repeatedly declared it will reject any U.N. resolution
that falls short of total and conditionally lifting of the
sanctions imposed on the country following its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No peace in South Asia Without Kashmir Solution: Musharraf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Chief Executive
General Pervaiz Musharraf Saturday said that lasting peace and
stability in South Asia is not possible without the solution of
the core issue of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Presiding over the 30th session of the Azad Jammu and Kashmir (
Pakistan-controlled part of Kashmir) Council here, he said
relations between Pakistan and India cannot be improved without
settlement of the Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
There is daily fire along the Line of Control which divides the
Kashmir between Pakistan and India, and existing tension between
the two countries which indicate Kashmir is a major source of
tension between the two countries, Musharraf said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Pakistan is willing to solve the issue
through peaceful means "if India shows sincerity" in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Musharraf said Pakistan will "continue to extend
political, moral and diplomatic support to the struggling people
of Kashmir for their right to self-determination".
</P>
<P>
"It was our duty to resolve the Kashmir dispute in accordance
with the aspirations of the people of Jammu and Kashmir and under
the U.N. resolutions," he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by a number of cabinet ministers from
Musharraf's government and senior officials of the Pakistan-
controlled Kashmir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
