<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Central Bank Urged To Reduce Interest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe National Chamber
of Commerce (ZNCC) has urged the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe to
reduce interest rates so as to stimulate the private sector in the
country.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the Zimbabwe News Agency on Saturday, ZNCC
President Nhlanhla Masuku said the current punitive interest rates
of over 60 percent prevailing on the market are stifling business
growth and worsening unemployment and poverty levels in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"Hard hit are the small to medium enterprises and
non-exporting firms who cannot access cheaper offshore loans
facilities," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Masuku, the latest statistics show that the broad
money supply growth has decreased from 53.7 percent in July to 42
percent in October this year.
</P>
<P>
"This slowdown in monetary growth, coupled with expectations of
lower inflation in the new millennium, justifies a reduction in
the repo rate, which will result in other rates moving down in
sympathy," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said a tight monetary policy stance characterized by high
interest rates will not achieve the objective of price stability
unless it is accompanied by fiscal prudence.
</P>
<P>
"As we have pointed out before, the government is never
discouraged from domestic borrowing despite the high interest
rates. This has resulted in a serious domestic debt problem, which
has seen a 29 percent of total government expenditure being
diverted from productive purposes to meet interest payments on
this debt," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The chamber firmly urges the authorities to ensure that a
reduction in interest rates is a key figure of the millennium
economic recovery program," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
