<HEADLINE> Fuel Prices Hike by 20 Percent in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Zambia increased its fuel
prices by 20 percent from mid-night of Friday, citing devaluation
of its currency Kwacha as the main reason for the price hike.
</P>
<P>
After the price hike, a litre of petrol is sold at 1,861 Kwacha
(about 0. 72 U.S. dollar) and diesel at 1,735 Kwacha a litre.
</P>
<P>
Some of the filling stations in the capital city are still hit
by petrol shortage.
</P>
<P>
Public Relations Officer of the Energy Regulation Board (ERB)
Faidess Simunza was quoted by Zambia Daily Mail as saying here
Saturday that the hike has been prompted by the devaluation of
Kwacha.
</P>
<P>
Other factors taken into consideration are the global petroleum
price increase of an average of 37 percent between July and
December this year, said the officer.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia had to import petrol in foreign exchanges during
this period. 
</P>
