<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand Gears Up Y2K Preparation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 18 (Xinhua) -- With the clock ticking toward
a new millennium, Thailand has found itself in a rather
comfortable situation in countering the so-called Year 2000, or
Y2K, computer problem.
</P>
<P>
Y2K, also dubbed as millennium bug, is expected to hit older
computers that still use two digits to represent years, like 99
for 1999. There are fears that once 2000 arrives, computers could
mistake it for 1900, causing them to produce flawed data or crash.
</P>
<P>
As early as in April 1998, the Thai government had already
realized the risks that might result from the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
It then appointed the National Electronics and Computer
Technology Center to be the core agency in giving advice and
knowledge on the bug to government agencies as well as private
sector.
</P>
<P>
A National Y2K Coordinating Committee was later established to
tackle the problem. A deputy prime minister, Trairong Suwannakhiri,
was appointed to head the committee.
</P>
<P>
The government also set aside some 14 billion baht (363.6
million U.S. dollars) to correct the Y2K problems in government
agencies and state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the committee announced that all crucial
agencies in the public sector, including 31 organizations
providing essential public services and utilities, are 100 percent
Y2K compliant.
</P>
<P>
These organizations cover electricity and energy sector,
banking,
finance and insurance sector, telecommunication and transport
sector and social services sector.
</P>
<P>
In general, the committee said, the public and state
enterprises and organizations are deemed 80 to 100 percent Y2K
compliant.
</P>
<P>
As for the private sector, the tackling of Y2K problem is
linked to the image of the enterprises, prompting the sector to
take a more active stance.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey found that most large Thai factories,
especially those with foreign partners, are well prepared for the
bug.
</P>
<P>
Keeping its image in mind, Thai Airways International (THAI),
though a state enterprise, has taken pains to counter any
millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, THAI spent about 300 million baht (7.5
million dollars) and deployed some 400 specialized personnel to
prepare for potential Y2K problems, its president Thamnoon Wanglee
revealed.
</P>
<P>
In October this year, the airline launched a 90-minute
simulation of a regular flight on the eve of January 1, 2000, with
Transport Minister Suthep Thaugsuban and other ministry officials
on board.
</P>
<P>
After the test, THAI announced that the national carrier is 100
percent Y2K compliant and its navigation, communications and all
flying systems will work normally when the clock strikes 12 at
midnight December 31.
</P>
<P>
However, risks are high in many small and medium-sized
enterprises, which lack funds to counter the millennium bug due to
a liquidity crunch resulting from the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
These companies, particularly in the petrochemical industry,
are expected to be temporarily closed on December 31 and January 1
to avoid danger to life and property.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, they might face legal action from the authorities,
the government said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand now has been at high gear in drafting measures to
prepare for possible emergency situation at the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the 14 billion baht fund, the government has also
set aside three billion baht (77.9 million dollars) as an
emergency fund.
</P>
<P>
A Y2K National Command Center, located at the head office of
the Telephone Organization of Thailand, will be opened on December
29.
</P>
<P>
From noon on December 30, more than 100 staff will be stationed
at the command center to coordinate and monitor potential risks
around-the-clock. About 100,000 others will be deployed nationwide
to monitor the situation.
</P>
<P>
A 24-hour Y2K hotline has also been set up to provide useful
information about the bug and instructions under emergency
situation.
</P>
<P>
Any public complaints or legal matters relating to Y2K
compliance will be handled by the Consumer Protection Board and
the Mediation Center on Year 2000 Problems, which is under the
Justice Ministry.
</P>
<P>
A final test will be run on December 29 to assess the readiness
of the country.
</P>
<P>
After having done what it is able to do, Thailand now prays for
a smooth transition to the new millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
