<HEADLINE> Manila to Well Implement Foreign-Assisted Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said Saturday that his administration will vigorously
pursue foreign-assisted projects to ensure their full and speedy
implementation.
</P>
<P>
In a statement in his weekly radio-TV program here, Estrada
said that it was during his administration that several problem-
plagued foreign-assisted projects moved forward.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue all these projects. We are doing our best to
push through with these," he said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said that he constantly keeps in touch with Director
General Felipe Medalla of the National Economic and Development
Authority to monitor the progress of foreign-assisted projects and
ensure that they are carried out on schedule.
</P>
<P>
Estrada was reacting to local press reports that the Asian
Development Bank, the World Bank and the Japan Bank for
International Cooperation will cut loans for the Philippines
because it failed to fully implement foreign-assisted projects.
</P>
<P>
In the same program, Medalla said that contrary to such reports,
there was no threat at all from the country's major aid donors to
put on hold pending loans to the Philippine government.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, he said, officials of the Philippine government
and the Asian Development Bank, the World Bank and the Japan Bank
for International Cooperation forged an agreement aimed at quickly
putting on track the implementation of existing projects funded by
these three donors. 
</P>
