<P>
Demonstrators shouted slogans "lift the sanctions now", "reject
the U.N. resolution", "end the sufferings of the Iraqi people" on
Baghdad's Ramadan 14th street, a famous downtown street.
</P>
<P>
Shalaan, one of the protestors, told Xinhua that Iraqis have
suffered too much under the embargo, but the U.S. and Britain do
not want to lift it, instead they want to prolong the suffering of
the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
So far the Iraqi government has not responded officially to the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Friday adopted a new comprehensive
policy on Iraq with 11 votes for and four abstentions. China,
Russia and France, three of the five permanent members of the
Council and Malaysia, one of the 10 non-permanent members,
abstained from voting.
</P>
<P>
The resolution stipulates the establishment of a new arms
control body -- the U.N. Monitoring, Verification and Inspection
Commission (UNMOVIC) -- in Iraq, and offers Iraq the chance to have
the trade sanctions suspended if it cooperates fully with the arms
inspectors and makes progress on key disarmament tasks to be
defined by the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has repeatedly declared it will reject any U.N.
resolution that falls short of a total and unconditional lifting of
the sanctions imposed on the country following its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Under the new U.N. resolution, immediately after itis adopted,
the ceiling will be lifted on how much oil Iraq can sell, now set
at 5.2 billion U.S. dollars every six months under an oil-for-food
program, and restrictions on its imports of humanitarian supplies
will be eased. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
