<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF to Resume Suspended Aid to Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) has agreed to lift the hurdles for final negotiations
with the Kenyan government on the resumption of aid, Nairobi's
newspapers reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Finance Minister Chris Okemo, who announced the decision
on Friday, said a team from the IMF will visit Kenya in January
next year for detailed negotiations for a possible resumption of
the 2.05-million-U.S. dollar aid package suspended in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
He said the IMF move is a recognition of the efforts made by
the Kenyan government in meeting the conditions set for loan
resumption to the East African country.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the IMF's Deputy Director for Africa
Goodall Gondwe is already in Kenya and will give the details of
the decision to Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Since the IMF suspended the aid to Kenya two years ago, the
country's economy has undergone serious deterioration with massive
withdrawal of foreign investors. Consequently, the country's
growth rate dropped from 2.3 percent in 1997 to 1.8 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
This year's economic growth is expected to be about 1.4 percent
as a result of depressed economic activity in all sectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
