<HEADLINE> Uganda Denies Ferrying Military Supplies With U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan State Minister for
Defense Steven Kavuma has refuted an allegation by the rebels of
the Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) that the government is using
convoys of humanitarian assistance to ferry military supplies.
</P>
<P>
"This is a lie," Kavuma told Xinhua in a telephone interview on
Saturday morning. "We have enough means to transport our troops
and support. We know the international convention and we can't
infringe them."
</P>
<P>
A report run by Saturday's Monitor daily said that the ADF
rebels have issued a two-page warning to the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees and the International Committee of the
Red Cross, claiming that some of the relief including dry rations
and medical supplies, have been diverted to military purposes.
</P>
<P>
The ADF rebels have been launching a series of surprise attacks
on Uganda's security and civilian targets in the western districts
of Bundibugyo, Kasese and Kabarole, killing more than 20 people.
</P>
<P>
The government troops are said to be squeezing the rebels's
space in a bid to kill them. Kavuma recognized the difficulty of
the task, saying the different terrain in the region is providing
make-shift sanctuary for the rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
