<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Teenage Girls More HIV Positive Than Boys: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Recent studies in Africa have
shown that girls aged between 15-19 are about eight times more
likely to be HIV positive than boys of the same age, a report from
the Joint United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS) said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report published by Saturday's Zambia Daily
Mail newspaper, women aged between 20 and 24 are three times more
likely to be infected with HIV than men of their age.
</P>
<P>
Launched by United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) resident
representative Peter McDermott, the report also said that women
aged 15-49 represent 43 percent of all new HIV infections, up from
40 percent two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The report attributes girls' vulnerability to biological,
social and economical weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, very few young people receive the
accurate and appropriate information they need about AIDS and its
transmission.
</P>
<P>
UNAIDS observed that the protection of the rights of girls and
women is critical in the context of AIDS, especially their rights
to set the terms of their own sexual activity, including its
safety and to refuse to sex altogether. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Arrests 14 Suspected Terrorists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has arrested 14 members of
a suspected extremist group which are based in Afghanistan but had
been planning terrorist attacks in the kingdom, the semi-official
Jordan Times Reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The number of the detainees rose to 14 after Pakistan extradited
a Jordanian, identified as Khalil Deek, to the kingdom on Thursday
at the request of Amman, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Deek is also wanted by Washington, but Jordan made the
extradition request first, so he was handed over to Amman, Jordan
Times said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Jordanian security forces arrested 11
Jordanians, one Iraqi and one Algerian who had entered the kingdom
on forged passports after receiving military training in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
All the 14 detainees were believed to be affiliated with a group
headed by the Afghanistan-based Saudi Arabian billionaire Osama Ben
Laden, who Washington said had masterminded last year's twin
bombings of American embassies in Kenya and Tanzania that killed
224 people, including 12 Americans.
</P>
<P>
The suspects arrested in Jordan possibly will be charged with
planning bomb attacks on tourism sites, new millennium celebrations
and American targets in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Statement Department warned Americans last week to be
cautious during Christmas and New Year holidays, because of
evidence of possible terrorist attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
