<HEADLINE> Uganda's Ex-Rebels Back Home From Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- A total of 30 former Ugandan
rebels, operating from Kenya, have returned home following the
government's Amnesty Bill passed by the Parliament on December 7.
</P>
<P>
The ex-rebels from the Lord's Resistance Army, Ninth October
Movement and Uganda United Front were received at Malaba border
post by officials of a Norwegian non-governmental organization
"Give Me a Chance" on Friday, the New Vision paper reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The officials with the NGO said that the return of the rebels
was coordinated by the Norwegian government and the Ugandan High
Commission in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
All exiles in Kenya are ready to return home following the
bill, Chairman of the Ugandan Rebel Groups in Kenya Yusuf Masinde
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the Amnesty Bill, all rebels would be pardoned and
 retrained for settling in society if they surrender themselves to
the government.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 ex-rebels are receiving training in the northern
part of the country. Those under 18 would probably be sent to
schools for more education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
