<HEADLINE> Japan Leads in Kenyan Car Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Japanese vehicles now dominate
the car market in Kenya, accounting for at least 50 percent of the
local car sales, the East African Standard newspapers reported on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 7,535 vehicles sold in the first 11 months this year,
Toyata brand took the top notch by 1,188 units, accounting for 16
percent of the country's overall motor vehicle sales, according to
statistics from Kenya Motor Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
The second position went to Nissan brand with the total sales
reaching 1, 090 units, or a market share of 14.5 percent. Isuzu
ranked the third with 1,074 units sold, securing 14.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi-SCM took the fourth place with 980 vehicles sold.
Land Rover came the fifth with 646 units sold and Peugeot the
sixth after selling 493 vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Mazda edged to the seventh position in market share after
selling 242 units. 
</P>
