<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health Experts Stress Compliance With Doctor's Advice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Do exactly what your
doctor suggested, your health will benefit much from it, the
American Heart Association said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Noncompliance with doctor's advice is a nation-wide hidden
health threat to the Americans, especially people with chronic
diseases, according to the association, the largest voluntary
health organization fighting cardiovascular disease and stroke.
</P>
<P>
More than half of all Americans with chronic diseases, such as
high blood pressure, do not follow their physician's medication
and lifestyle guidance, the association said.
</P>
<P>
The patients are usually told to take appropriate medical
treatment including diet, exercise, smoking cessation and
medication by healthcare provider. But 12 percent of all
prescriptions are never filled and more than half of all
prescription medications are taken improperly.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a recent study published in the Journal of the American
Medical Association, the association said that people who act as
doctor's advice to maintain low blood pressure and cholesterol
levels and to abstain smoking can add six to nine-and-a-half years
to their lives, compared to those who are less careful about their
health.
</P>
<P>
To heighten the public awareness of the importance of
compliance, the American Heart Association, with some four million
volunteers, has begun a campaign called the Compliance Action
Program. The program is aimed at physicians, nurses, pharmacists,
other allied health professionals and healthcare organizations, as
well as patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Bans Export Of Petrol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has
banned petrol export in any container other than a tank fixed to a
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
The move announced on Friday is designed to stop people
illegally exporting the fuels such as petrol and paraffin which
are cheaper in the country than in neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
Noting that a number of people were buying paraffin and petrol
in Zimbabwean currency and exporting, Minister of Industry and
Commerce Nathan Shamuyarira stressed: "It is now illegal to export
petrol in any container other than a tank fixed to a vehicle and
paraffin in any container."
</P>
<P>
The disturbing thing was that foreigners were making several
trips a day to neighboring countries selling these products, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that "our fuel" on the domestic market was
cheaper compared to its neighboring countries because the
government subsidizes the commodities, particularly paraffin, to
make them affordable to local consumers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
