<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Pledges Reconstruction Fund for E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Australia would contribute 25
million Australian dollars (16.5 million U.S. dollars) this
financial year to help East Timor in its reconstruction, Foreign
Minister Alexander Downer said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Downer said in a statement the money would be sent to an
international reconstruction and development trust fund and the
United Nations Trust Fund.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian government has strongly supported East Timor
through the largest emergency humanitarian program ever undertaken
by Australia," Downer said.
</P>
<P>
The figure is part of the 528 million U.S. dollars pledged by
international donors at a meeting in Tokyo last Friday to help
East Timor's reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
An assessment report to the Tokyo meeting said rebuilding the
civil service, particularly the health and education systems, and
rebuilding essential services and infrastructure and support for
agriculture were priorities.
</P>
<P>
Downer said the East Timorese had also identified
reconciliation within their communities and the establishment of
the rule of law as urgent priorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
