<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Railway Rules out Y2K-Related Disruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Service users of the Bangladesh
Railway (BR) could rest assured with the dawning of the new
millennium, as the authorities have ruled out possibilities of
major service disruptions, The Financial Express reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"By and large, passenger and cargo operations of BR are
expected to be free from the cyber havoc as all the major
equipment requiring Y2K compliance have already undergone
necessary tests," BR director general Atikul Hossain Khan was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most of the software used in the operation of the railway was
now compliant, while some hardware still required compliance, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Of the hardware, control devices of locomoting and generating
sets, and signaling and train-control systems were still to be
fully compliant. "We are now regularly examining the hardware base
and trying our best to achieve compliance," the director general
said, ruling out any major fiasco on this account.
</P>
<P>
He added that even if hardware compliance was not attained in
due time, services would face any setback as adequate backup
support systems have already been put in place.
</P>
<P>
The computerized wagon control system, one of the major
automated components of BR, was already Y2K compliant and the
cargo operations of the BR was totally free from the Y2K scare,
while in the passenger service area, the only thing requiring
compliance was its seat reservation and ticketing system, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bridge to Link China, Europe, Latin World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Macao is training managers from
80 small businesses in the Chinese mainland for a business trip to
Europe in next March. In return, an European economic and trade
delegation will then go to the inland areas of China via Macao for
discussions about technology transfer and investment in China.
</P>
<P>
Macao has become a link between the 1.2 billion Chinese people
and the one-sixth of world population who speak the Latin
languages, said Gary Mei-Cheong Ngai, executive director of the
Latin Foundation of Macao.
</P>
<P>
Taking advantage of the unique cultural background of Macao
that has enjoyed close ties with the Latin world over the past
four and half centuries, Ngai is organizing exchanges of visits
between the business circles from the two major potential markets
in the world, namely China and the Latin world including south
Europe, Africa and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Since Macao is a free port located in the heart of the fastest
growing region in the world, the European Union (EU) has set up
its first Asian business consultation center in Macao.
</P>
<P>
In May 1992, the EU signed a trade cooperation agreement with
Macao. In 1993, the EU established partnership with Macao under
its international investment plan, encouraging exchanges between
small businesses in Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Macao has set up an European Research Center,
with trade and economic representative offices opened in Lisbon of
Portugal and Brussels of Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Latin America is also trying to use Macao as a gateway to the
Asia-Pacific market.
</P>
<P>
The Macao government has already set up the Macao Trade and
Investment Promotion Institute and the Macao Productivity and
Technology Transfer Center in order to facilitate information flow
between Macao and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
It has also been using the wide connection of overseas Chinese
and Macao-born Portuguese to reduce the gap between business
people from different continents.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the non-profitable Latin Foundation of Macao has
done a fruitful job since it was set up in 1997, Ngai said that
the private organization is planning to host a seminar on
exploring the markets in Latin America and China next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Continue Increase of Investment in Macao, French Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Consul General of France in
Hong Kong and Macao Jerome Pasquier said in a recent interview
that France firmly supports China's resumption of sovereignty over
Macao and will continue to increase French investment in Macao
after its return.
</P>
<P>
Pasquier said that he is confident about the future of Macao
and its return to China will bring new opportunities for French
businesses there.
</P>
<P>
Pasquier believed that Macao's return to the motherland will be
in a very positive direction of development and the "One Country,
Two Systems" concept will work well in Macao as it did in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
"It will be a historic date, and China's recovery of
administration over Macao at the turn of the century is a good
symbol," Pasquier said. "I totally share the great joy and
pleasure with the Chinese people over the news."
</P>
<P>
As an Envoy, Pasquier has traveled frequently between Hong Kong
and Macao since he took office in Hong Kong last year. He has also
met with Edmund Ho Hau Wah, chief executive-designate of the Macao
Special Administrative Region (MSAR) several times.
</P>
<P>
"The people of Macao are very optimistic of Macao's future, and
the new team of capable MSAR leaders have lots of new ideas to run
things well," he recalled.
</P>
<P>
With its unique multi-cultural backgrounds and scenic
attractions, Macao is an international city. And Macao's return
will benefit not only its own economic development and social
stability, but also the foreign trade and investment there, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The French government has attached great importance over Macao'
s return to China and will send a high-level delegation to attend
the ceremony in Macao since France is the biggest European
investor in Macao except Portugal, Pasquier said.
</P>
<P>
"We have had a rather good economic presence in Macao and we
have many French companies in Macao in dealing with water supply,
electricity, waste treatment, air transport, hotel and
entertainment," Pasquier said, adding that Macao's return to China
will provide a good basis for France to increase its trade and
investment.
</P>
<P>
"There is no reason to change our foreign policy since the
system of Macao will remain unchanged," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
