<HEADLINE> Macao Newspaper Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Following are leading news
stories in major Chinese language newspapers in Macao on Saturday,
a two-day countdown to Macao's return to the motherland and the
establishment of the Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR) of
China.
</P>
<P>
Macao Daily News
</P>
<P>
-- Sources with the Macao visa office of China's Ministry of
Foreign Affairs said Friday that 43 countries will retain their
consular representations in Macao after China resume the exercise
of sovereignty over the region.
</P>
<P>
-- The fact of Macao's return to the motherland indicates that
the principles of "peaceful reunification" and "one country, two
systems" are the practical method and the best way to resolve the
Taiwan issue, according to Wang Qiren, director of the Xinhua News
Agency Macao Branch.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Foreign Minster Tang Jiaxuan arrived in Macao Friday
night to attend Macao's power handover ceremony to be held at
midnight of Sunday.
</P>
<P>
-- Singapore will give visa-free access to holders of passports
issued by the Macao SAR, sources with the Singapore Immigration
and Registration (SIR) announced Friday. Singapore was the first
country to make such an announcement. In addition, 18 other
countries have declared to acknowledge the Macao SAR passport.
</P>
<P>
-- Friday was the last working day of the Portuguese government,
and some 18,000 civil servants spent the day peacefully as usual.
The Macao SAR government will begin its first working day on
December 23 after the handover.
</P>
<P>
 Jornal Va Kio
</P>
<P>
-- The chief executive-designate of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (SAR) Edmund Ho Hau Wah on Friday appointed
members of provisional municipal councils of the Macao SAR. The
members will assume office as China resumes the exercise of
sovereignty over Macao on December 20.
</P>
<P>
-- Chief Executive-designate of the Macao SAR Edmund Ho Hau Wah
Friday appointed the director of the Information Office of the SAR.
</P>
<P>
Tai Chung Pou
</P>
<P>
-- Portuguese President Jorge Sampaio arrived in Macao Friday
afternoon to attend the Macao handover ceremony, which is to be
held at midnight of December 19.
</P>
<P>
-- The two chief representatives of both Chinese and Portuguese
sides of the Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison Group held their last
meeting Friday and reached consensus on some issues including the
transfer of archives and assets of the Portuguese Macao government.
</P>
</TEXT>
