<HEADLINE> Stormy Winds Hit Southern Scandinavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Stormy winds battered the
southern part of the Scandinavia Peninsula, especially southern
Sweden and Norway, Friday, disrupting electricity transmission,
forcing the closure of roads and delaying flights and ferry
operation.
</P>
<P>
The strong winds resulting from low atmospheric pressure above
the Atlantic Ocean hit the southern part of Scandinavia during the
day, and gained strength in the evening with a maximum speed of 34
meters per second.
</P>
<P>
The winds destroyed some houses and caused serious damage to
power transmission facilities. More than 10,000 residents
suffered a blackout in the southern part of Sweden.
</P>
<P>
The winds also forced the suspension of most ferry operations
in southern Sweden, Denmark, Germany and Poland, and Norway had to
close 22 roads.
</P>
<P>
About 20,000 passengers in Norway were affected as flights were
delayed or canceled, including 4,000 stranded at the airport in
Oslo.
</P>
<P>
Scandinavia has seen abnormal weather since the end of November.
Most parts of Sweden were attacked by strong winds on November 29-
30 and the country's southern part and the whole of Denmark were
hit by a hurricane that caused huge economic losses on December 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
