<HEADLINE> Heavy Storms Hit Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Repeated heavy storms have
recently hit most parts of Yugoslavia, cutting off power and water
supplies, traffic and telephone service in some regions.
</P>
<P>
By mid-Friday, the Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported, it had
snowed over 24 hours in the northern and central regions of Serbia,
where snows had accumulated to 20 centimeters in depth, and even
up to one meter in some parts, paralyzing road traffic in many
places.
</P>
<P>
In Montenegro, continuous heavy snowfalls and rainfalls have
caused floods and blocked traffic. In the Montenegro capital city
of Podgorica, several hundreds families have been evacuated from
the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
In the northwestern town of Pljevlja, with 50 centimeters of
snow, public traffic routes were all blocked. Since midnight
Thursday, power supply and telephone service to half of the city
proper have been cut off. The provision of bread and milk has
been interrupted since early Friday.
</P>
<P>
Heavy snowfalls also hit neighboring Bosnia-Herzegovina,
causing traffic blockade and cut-off of power and water supplies
in some areas, it was reported.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian meteorological authorities said the snowfalls
across Bosnia starting Wednesday have been the heaviest in more
than a decade.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian press reported Friday that in the capital city of
Sarajevo, it had snowed more than one meter deep on streets by the
day, forcing people to walk to their work sites. Ten regions of
the city suffered cut-off of power and water supplies. Meanwhile,
inconvenient traffic has affected market supply, in particular
that of vegetables.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
