<HEADLINE> Indonesian Sports Council Sets Date For Olympics Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's National Sports
Council (KONI) announced the centralized training program for the
Sydney Olympic Games would begin on February 1.
</P>
<P>
KONI official in charge of athlete development Mochamad
Hindartosaid each sport with athletes who had qualified for the
Olympics or were still competing in Olympic qualifying tournaments
should send their athletes to the program.
</P>
<P>
"The Olympic Games are getting closer. The centralized training
program must begin at the latest on February 1. If we begin later
than that we will only have a little time for making adjustments
in the training he was quoted by the Jakarta Post Saturday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"The athletes will be invited to join the training program by
the end of December. After the Idul Fitri holiday we will start
the physical and health tests," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Idul Fitri is the feast to celebrate the success of Muslim
in adhering to Islamic principles during Ramadhan -- the month
which marks God's revelation of the holy Qur'an to the Prophet
Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
Hindarto said he would discuss the training program with
experts from the council's research and development department.
</P>
<P>
"We will ask the experts to help us prepare the training
program for the athletes, so we can get them in peak condition for
the Olympics," he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has qualified 13 athletes for the Olympics, scheduled
to be held in Sydney next September.
</P>
<P>
National shuttlers have until April 30 to qualify for the
Olympicsand the Badminton Association of Indonesia hopes to
qualify 24 shuttlers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
