<HEADLINE> Roundup: Settlement of Macao Issue Ushers in New Era for Sino- Portuguese Relations (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What Deng said has played a guiding role ever since. Effective
cooperation between China and Portugal has contributed to a smooth
transition for Macao and its smooth return to China.
</P>
<P>
The going into force on January 15, 1988 of the Sino-Portugese
Joint Declaration marked the beginning of a transitional period
for Macao, a transition from Portuguese to Chinese rule. Over the
past 12 years, the two sides have joined hands in resolving a
series of major transition-related issues.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin has pointed out, on different
occasions, that, in tackling the Macao issue, leaders of the two
nations should "take a strategic stand." He said: "The higher one
stands, the farther one can see. Ensuring a smooth transfer of
power in Macao accords with the fundamental interests of both
China and Portugal."
</P>
<P>
Portuguese President Jorge Sampaio speaks highly of the
cooperation between the two countries on the Macao issue, saying
that the Joint Declaration has set the orientation for Macao's
development, that the two countries have undertaken their
respective responsibilities and honored their commitments, and
that the results of their cooperation are very positive."
</P>
<P>
Edmund Ho Hau Wah attributes Macao's smooth transition to
mutual trust and cooperation between China and Portugal, whose
governments have both adopted a responsible attitude toward
resolving standing issues during the period of transition and have
achieved good results.
</P>
<P>
Observers here point out that it is mutual trust and
cooperation between the two countries that has created conditions
necessary for the implementation of the policies of "one country,
two systems," "Macao people governing Macao" and "a high degree
autonomy" for Macao.
</P>
</TEXT>
