<HEADLINE> Tianjin Striving to Improve Air Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Factories in the coastal city
of Tianjin in north China face shutdowns if they fail to meet
State standards on waste discharge by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,782 enterprises are targets of the campaign that
aims to halt further deterioration of air quality in the city,
today's China Daily said, quoting sources with the Tianjin
Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The State Environmental Protection Administration demanded all
industries across the country stop discharging excessive
pollutants into the environment before the end of next year.
Tianjin actively responded to the demand and has set its own
deadline one year ahead.
</P>
<P>
Until now, about 99 percent of the enterprises in Tianjin have
been meeting the pollution control standard.
</P>
<P>
Others are cutting it close, running the risk of being put out
of business.
</P>
<P>
Most of the offending factories produce steel, cement,
pesticides, leather or starch, an official of the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
The port city, which used to serve as a major industrial base
of north China, has achieved great improvements in its air quality.
</P>
</TEXT>
