<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Election Campaign Enters Final Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's much heated
presidential election campaign entered the final day on Saturday
with the two main contestants holding their last rallies in the
capital Colombo.
</P>
<P>
President Chandrika Kumaratunga, who was seeking reelection,
will hold her final rally at the Colombo Town Hall grounds on
Saturday night, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Her main rival Ranil Wickremesinghe of the main opposition
United National Party (UNP) will also wind up his campaign with a
rally in Colombo Central at Maradana.
</P>
<P>
The election, to be held 11 months earlier than previously
scheduled November next year, is being contested by a record 13
contenders including four independent candidates.
</P>
<P>
However, it is believed that the main battle will be fought
between Kumaratunga and Wickremesinghe. Both have expressed
confidence of winning the election.
</P>
<P>
About 11.779 million people are eligible to vote next Tuesday
in the island country's fourth presidential election to choose a
president to take Sri Lanka to the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
In the run-up to the election, poll-related violence was
mounting. The Police Election Secretariat said by Friday afternoon
poll-related violence amounted to 977 since the nominations were
filed on November 16,
</P>
<P>
To curb the rising violence, acting Elections Commissioner D.M.
P.B. Dassanayake said Friday that no public meeting shall be held
during the period commencing midnight of Saturday and ending one
week after the declaration of the result of the poll.
</P>
<P>
On the invitation of the Election Commissioner's Department, 26
foreign observers arrived Colombo this week to monitor the poll.
They began discussions Friday with the authorities and candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
