<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based Newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China's Central Military Commission held a symposium Friday
to commemorate the 100th birthday of Nie Rongzhen (1899-1992), a
late marshal and founder of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (
PLA) and New China.
</P>
<P>
At the symposium, Chinese President and Chairman of the Central
Military Commission (CMC) Jiang Zemin spoke highly of Nie's great
contributions to the Chinese people's liberation and socialist
construction.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin, CMC Vice-Chairman Zhang Wannian and
CMC Vice-Chairman and Defense Minister Chi Haotian recently wrote
inscriptions for the PLA troops to be stationed in the Macao
Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
-- China's National People's Congress Standing Committee held
its 13th session and approved the make-up of its Basic Law
Committee for the Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR) Friday.
It was presided over by Li Peng, chairman of the Standing
Committee of the NPC.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- The Supreme People's Court held a meeting at the Great Hall
of the People yesterday to celebrate its 50th birthday. The
meeting received congratulatory letters from top Chinese leaders
Jiang Zemin, Li Peng, Zhu Rongji and Li Ruihuan.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin and NPC Chairman Li Peng met with
visiting Czech Prime Minister Milos Zeman here Friday. Jiang said
that the further consolidation of China-Czech relations is in the
interests of both countries.
</P>
<P>
-- The preparatory body for the establishment of the Macao
Special Administrative Region (SAR) has fulfilled its tasks since
it became operational on May 5 last year, according to Qian Qichen,
chairman of the Macao SAR's Preparatory Committee under the NPC.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Director Wang Qiren of the Xinhua News Agency Macao Branch
has said the return of Macao is as important as that of Hong Kong
in 1997 although Macao is much smaller in size and population, and
Macao's return will be the second step toward the peaceful
reunification of China.
</P>
