<HEADLINE> Private Clinics To Be Protected in Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 18 (Xinhua)-- Private clinics in Macao can
continue their business as usual and the rights and interests of
private doctors will be protected according to the Basic Law of
Macao Special Administrative Region (MSAR) after the territory's
return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Days before the handover the Licensing Office of the Macao
Health Services is still receiving applications for the open of
private clinics.
</P>
<P>
Miss Leong Pui San of the office now has got more than 70
applications to process.
</P>
<P>
Luo Xiaojin of the Association of Medicine of Macao said
private clinics, which are distributed in the residential areas,
treat over one half of patients in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show there are 444 medical doctors, most of whom
Chinese, working in private clinics of the region.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 civil servants working in the Health Services
department of the government run their own clinics or are part-
time doctors.
</P>
<P>
Most of the medical doctors in Macao are trained outside Macao,
mostly in the Chinese mainland, because Macao does not have any
medical school.
</P>
<P>
There is only one government-run hospital, Conde de Sao
Januario, and one private hospital, Kiang Wu, in Macao. The lack
of doctors, high expenses and language barriers have led to the
increase of private clinics and certified doctors.
</P>
<P>
Luo held that the private clinics will not be affected by but
benefit from the handover since the clinics will have more
opportunities to conduct exchanges and cooperation with mainland
professionals.
</P>
<P>
Macao's public health services have been improving in recent
years. The government has set up eight health care centers to
provide free medical services.
</P>
<P>
"This situation poses challenges to the private clinics," Luo
said. However, he believes the competition will help the residents
get better services.
</P>
<P>
Macao, with a population of 430,000, has a relatively advanced
medical and health care system. The average life span of Macao
people, 77.5 for male and 81.2 for female, is above the world's
average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Groom Young Badminton Athletes in Provincial Chapters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Badminton Association of
Indonesia (PBSI) planned to groom young talented athletes in
provincial chapters.
</P>
<P>
"It's difficult for us to maintain a training method by
centralizing the athletes in a national center like we do now. It
takes a lot of funds and is ineffective," PBSI official in charge
of athletes development Mangombar Ferdinand Siregar said.
</P>
<P>
"PBSI will also recruit coaches for the chapters, who will be
given programs and targets similar to those we give to our coaches
in the center. We will ask them to groom young athletes based on
the center's training standards. Some chapters have requested
authority to stage the training when they attended the national
congress in Semarang, Central Java, earlier this month," he said.
</P>
<P>
By adopting the new method, he said, PBSI can observe their
progress by staging an annual tournament to decide their overall
rankings.
</P>
<P>
"We can also decide which international tournaments we will
send them to by looking at their national rankings," he said.
</P>
<P>
The new method would be more effective and efficient in seeking
younger potential talent, especially for the women's teams, he was
quoted by the Jakarta Post Saturday as saying.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, former world number one badminton player Susi
Susanti criticized PBSI by saying that it should have recruited
younger players, aged between 14 and 16 years old, despite
admitting winners of national tournaments.
</P>
<P>
"Generally, I agree with Susi's opinion because if we don't
groom the younger players as soon as possible, it will be too late
for them to reach international standards of playing," Siregar
said.
</P>
<P>
He said with the new method, PBSI would not need to have a
promotion and relegation system to pick the best players in the
center.
</P>
<P>
PBSI plans to expel six of its 66 players in the center this
month. Three senior women's shuttlers -- Susi, Mia Audina and
Meiluawati -- have withdrawn from the center. Susi withdrew due to
pregnancy, Miamoved to the Netherlands to follow her husband while
Meiluawati had to resign due to a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
Siregar said PBSI had focused its attention on five younger
athletes, who had yet to join the center, including girls singles
Chung Siang and boys singles Ignatius Rudy, who just won the
national championships in Semarang earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the annual recruitment system, which admitted
winners of national circuits, would be conducted on June 1 next
year.
</P>
<P>
Siregar said he also agreed with Susi's idea of not
specializing younger players in certain events.
</P>
<P>
"We have changed this for newly recruited players. However, we'
ll still have to observe their performance during training and
tournaments. We'll also have to discuss with players and coaches
the benefits they can gain by playing singles and doubles," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Siregar criticized the condition in the center's dormitories,
where most shuttlers had luxury cars and telephones in their rooms.
</P>
<P>
"This is an impact of metropolitan life. We can't resist it. We
call on them to open their hearts to know what their duty is," he
added 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
