<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of Diplomatic News (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Fijian Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry arrived in Beijing
Monday evening on an official visit to China, at the invitation of
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Zhu Rongji said Tuesday that the Chinese Government
is ready to make concerted efforts with the Fijian Government to
usher in stable Sino-Fijian relations of all-round cooperation in
the next century on the basis of the Five Principles of Peaceful
Co-existence, during talks with Fijian Prime Minister Mahendra
Chaudhry.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin, in a meeting with Fijian Prime
Minister Mahendra Chaudhry, said he believes that Chaudhry's China
visit will help promote the growth of Sino-Fijian friendly and
cooperative ties.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Chinese government treasures its ties with
Fiji, and at the turn of the century, the leaders of the two
countries should work together to push forward Sino-Fijian
relations established on the basis of the Five Principles of
Peaceful Co-Existence.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Vice President Visits China
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao said Wednesday that China
will work together with Brazil to promote their strategic
partnership and continue to make efforts for developing such
relations oriented towards the 21st century. Hu made the remarks
during talks with Brazilian Vice-President Marco Maciel who
arrived in Beijing for an official visit Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin, in a meeting Thursday with Brazilian
Vice-President Marco Maciel said that during the 25 years since
the forging of diplomatic relations, especially since 1993 when
the two countries established a strategic partnership, bilateral
cooperation in various fields has witnessed considerable
development.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the Chinese National People's Congress (
NPC) Standing Committee, also met with Vice-President Maciel
Thursday, and said that Sino-Brazilian relations have developed
soundly since diplomatic ties were forged 25 years ago.
</P>
