<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, December 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States and the European Union (EU)
ended their one-day summit here Friday, pledging to launch a new
round of global trade talks, increasing pressure on Russia over
Chechnya, but with trade disputes still remaining.
</P>
<P>
One of the statements issued after the summit said they
continued to be committed to launching a new round of global trade
talks in the aftermath of the failure to do so in Seattle at the
third ministerial meeting of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
EU Commission President Romano Prodi and Martti Ahtisaari, the
president of Finland, who now holds the six-month EU presidency,
attended the summit. The 15-member EU and the U.S. held a summit
semi-annually. (US-EU-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States failed to reach an agreement
with the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) in their
Berlin talks over the further joint search for the remains of U.S.
soldiers missing during the Korean War, the Pentagon said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Berlin talks, which lasted three days and broke up Friday
with no result, were aimed at setting a schedule for further joint
recovery operations in the DPRK countryside for the coming year.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have not yet set the date for further talks
despite the United States' anxiety for that agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon said the United States would continue efforts to
conclude the agreement "consistent with past arrangements." (US-
DPRK-MIA)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Security Council narrowly
adopted Friday a resolution which could resume U.N. weapons
inspections in Iraq under conditions of cooperation from Baghdad,
but three of the five permanent members of the council questioned
its enforceability with little hope for Iraq to have the sanctions
suspended, if not completely lifted.
</P>
<P>
The resolution passed 11-0, with abstentions by permanent
council members China, Russia and France, along with Malaysia,
dealing a heavy blow to the attempts by the United States and
Britain to show Iraq a unified stand of the council.
</P>
<P>
The resolution required nine votes and no veto to pass the
council which has been locked in debates for eight months. It sets
up a new arms inspection agency, named the U.N. Monitoring,
Verification and Inspection Commission (UNMOVIC), to replace the U.
N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) charged with dismantling Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction. (UN-Iraq) 
</P>
</TEXT>
