<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Offers Nazi-era Slave, Forced Laborers Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Germany Friday offered 10
billion marks (5.2 billion U.S. dollars) to compensate Nazi-era
slave and forced laborers.
</P>
<P>
German chief negotiator Otto Lambsdorff told a news conference
in Berlin on Friday that a meeting of victim groups in Washington
in February would try to determine the level of individual awards.
</P>
<P>
Slave laborers who were supposed to work to death in
concentration camps would receive a much larger amount of money
than forced laborers who were deported from their home countries
to work in Germany.
</P>
<P>
The 10 billion marks will be jointly raised by the federal
government, local governments and big companies.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 top German companies, many facing legal action for
using forced labor during the war, have joined a fund for this
purpose.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has pledged to protect German firms from
future U.S. action over their wartime past by issuing a
declaration urging courts not to take up new claims after the
payments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
