<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Timing of Macao Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 18 (Xinhua) -- On December 20, 1999, the
Chinese government will resume the exercise of sovereignty over
Macao. How was the date of Macao's return to the motherland
decided?
</P>
<P>
Years ago, the timing of Macao's return used to be an issue of
difference between China and Portugal. At the very beginning of
its negotiations with Portugal, China made it clear that taking
into consideration of the friendship between the two countries,
China will put an interval between the handover of Macao and that
of Hong Kong so that Macao will return to China one year later
than Hong Kong. That is to say, China will resume the exercise of
sovereignty over Macao in 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, the Portuguese side insisted that Macao should have a
longer transitional period than Hong Kong. In 1986, some
Portuguese even openly suggested that the date of Macao's return
to China should be in 2017, the 460th anniversary of the
occupation of Macao by the Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
In November, 1986, the two sides failed to reach an agreement
on the timing of Macao's return when the then Chinese Vice-Foreign
Minister Zhou Nan visited Portugal.
</P>
<P>
"Accomplishing the great cause of return of Hong Kong and Macao
to the motherland by the end of the 20th century is both the
aspiration of the Chinese people and the determination of the
Chinese government," Zhou told reporters at airport at the end of
his visit to Portugal.
</P>
<P>
On December 31, 1986, a Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman said
in a statement: "Resuming the exercise of sovereignty over Macao
before 2000 is the unshakable stand and aspiration of the one
billion Chinese people, including the compatriots in Macao. Any
proposition about Macao's return to China after 2000 are
unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government took such a strong stand that Macao be
returned to China by the end of the century that the Portuguese
government had to reconsider the timing of Macao's return.
</P>
<P>
In January, 1987, the State Council of Portugal held a plenary
meeting to discuss this issue. It was concluded at the meeting
that maintaining and promoting friendship and cooperation with the
People's Republic of China is of great significance for
safeguarding the stability and prosperity in Macao, and it was
agreed at the meeting that Portugal would handover Macao to China
on December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
China welcomed the decision that Portugal made. But at the same
time, China said that the date was too close to the year 2000 to
have time for handling many issues. China suggested that the
handover take place on December 20, 1999.
</P>
<P>
On March 7, 1987, Portuguese President Mario Alberto N. L.
Soares presided over another meeting of the State Council and
accepted China's proposal.
</P>
<P>
On April 13, 1987, China and Portugal signed an Joint
Declaration on the issue of Macao in the Great Hall of the People
in Beijing. The Joint Declaration points out explicitly that the
Macao region is part of the Chinese territory and that the
Government of the People's Republic of China will resume the
exercise of sovereignty over Macao on December 20, 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
