<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Sees Fine Progress By Italy in Public Account </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Italy can now take its place
beside four other EU countries who have sorted out their public
finances this decade by first raising taxes and then lowering them,
according to a new European Commission's (EC) report.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian news agency Ansa, in a still-unreleased
report on Italy's slow economic growth since 1990, the EC's
economic affairs division said that the improvement in the nations
' public finances had been "exceptional."
</P>
<P>
Italy's primary deficit - the part of public spending financed
by government bonds - has fallen by 9.5 percent this decade, twice
as much as any other European Union country, as a series of
deficit-slashing budgets have been implemented.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the budget-cutting came from higher taxation
concentrated around 1992-93, when the first European Monetary
Union crisis took place, and 1996-97, when Italy was chasing a
place in the euro.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, when Italian former Premier Silvio Berlusconi was in
power, the campaign to right accounts missed a beat or two, with "
a certain uncertainty in fiscal policy," the report said.
</P>
<P>
But from 1998, with public accounts vastly improved, the
emphasis had switched and governments had begun re-modulating the
tax system, reducing rates in many areas.
</P>
<P>
This approach to straightening finances mirrored the one
already been used to good effect by Germany, the netherlands,
Belgium and Spain, the EC said.
</P>
<P>
Hence, "Italy can, after a daily of four years, join the
countries who have adopted this switching strategy in restricting
the budget, "it continued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
