<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Antitrust Fines Coca Cola 30 Billion Lire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Italy's antitrust authority has
fined Coca Cola Italy 30.6 billion lire (about 16.5 million U.S.
dollars) for unfair business practices aimed at edging rival Pepsi
Cola out of a key sector of Italy's soft drinks market.
</P>
<P>
According to the authority, Coca Cola Italy offered weighty
incentives to pubs and bars to convert their draught cola taps
from Pepsi Cola to Coca Cola and gave preferential treatment to
wholesalers dealing in their beverage alone.
</P>
<P>
The moves were part of an illegal strategy "aimed at expelling
the principal competitor from the draught drinks section of the
market," abusing a position of dominance, a statement said.
</P>
<P>
Coca Cola and the Italian companies it controlled had the
national soft drinks market sewn up, the authority said, putting
the Atlanta-based company's market share at 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
The authority's investigation, which started from a complaint
by Pepsi Cola, also uncovered illegal practices by Socib and Sosib,
two Italian firms authorized to bottle Coca Cola.
</P>
<P>
The two companies were fined a total of 800 million lire (about
43,000 U.S. dollars) for imposing exclusive contracts on
wholesalers, who were thus forced to purchase all their supplies
of soft drinks in one place.
</P>
<P>
The authority ordered Coca Cola to "end such practices
immediately" and gave it four months to prepare a report outlining
action taken to remedy the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
