<HEADLINE> Ferguson 'Troublemaker' Slur Dismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Manchester United chairman
Martin Edwards described Friday claims of a rift between himself
and manager Sir Alex Ferguson as "nonsense".
</P>
<P>
The allegations appear in a new book - Manchester Unlimited -
by sports journalist Mihir Bose about BSkyB's attempted takeover
of the club.
</P>
<P>
Edwards is reported to have described Ferguson as a"
troublemaker" and questioned his ability to handle money.
</P>
<P>
Bose quotes a United insider who described Edwards' reaction
when BSkyB representative Sir Tim Bell suggested that Ferguson
should be kept informed of the takeover plans.
</P>
<P>
"Christ, no! You don't want to see him. He's a troublemaker,"
Edwards is quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"If you tell him, he'll leak everything. He's totally hostile
and I've just written him a letter warning him."
</P>
<P>
Edwards is also alleged to have reacted with similar horror
when it was suggested that Ferguson should benefit financially
from the takeover.
</P>
<P>
"Don't give him money, for Christ's sake. The man's useless,"
is what Edwards is supposed to have said.
</P>
<P>
This is not the first report that the two most powerful men in
Old Trafford do not have a close relationship.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson's own book Managing My Life, saw him admit that he
found the chairman hard to deal with, particularly over finance.
</P>
<P>
And Edwards has suggested in the past that it may be better for
the club if Ferguson moved on when his managerial career was over
rather than take a seat on the board.
</P>
<P>
The chairman has refused to comment in detail about the latest
claims.
</P>
<P>
"This is a load of nonsense," he was quoted by local media as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"I will not comment on hearsay or allegations in books," he
said. 
</P>
