<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Move Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 12.54 at 11,257.43. Early
in the session, the blue chip index rose as much as 138 points,
beating the record closing high of 11,326.04 set on August 25.
</P>
<P>
Broad stock indicators were mostly higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor'
s 500 index rose 2.25 at 1,421.03 and the technology heavy Nasdaq
composite index rose 38.00 at 3,753.06, surpassing the record
closing high of 3,715.06 points set Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Stocks rose after the Commerce Department reported that
construction of new homes and apartments fell by 2.3 percent in
November, the lowest level in seven months. Investors rushed into
the market in belief that hike in interest rates may have been
slowing the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised rates three times this year in
an effort to ward off inflation.
</P>
<P>
The market was also helped to move higher as GE announced a 3-
for-1 stock split and a plan to raise its dividend. The move gave
investors confidence in the company's prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 0.11 at 631.65 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 4.06 at 829.80. But the Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 0.95 at 466.21.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 8-to-7 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,682 up, 1,437 down and 460
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 1.35 billion shares from 1.07 billion
in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
