<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RUC Reforms to Start in New Year in N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Northern Ireland
Secretary of State Peter Mandelson said Friday that he will start
implementing the reforms of the Royal Ulster Constabulary in the
new year.
</P>
<P>
He said he also wanted to scale down security forces in the
province.
</P>
<P>
Writing in Friday's London Independent newspaper, the secretary
of state said he intended to implement the Patten proposals on
policing but he hoped "in a way that carried the support and
goodwill of both communities."
</P>
<P>
He wrote, "I am aware of the balance we must keep between, on
the one hand, scaling down the security forces' profile as quickly
as possible to reflect the huge change there has been in Northern
Ireland, while on the other, not leaving people vulnerable to
attack from dissidents on both sides who oppose progress."
</P>
<P>
A number of Patten's 175 proposals for policing reform raised
hostility from unionists in Northern Ireland, especially those
dealing with changes to the RUC's name and the badge which bears
the Irish harp and British Crown.
</P>
<P>
He said the government supported the report in principle but
key questions of how it was implemented, when it was implemented
and over what period remained to be taken by him.
</P>
<P>
When the Patten report was published in September, the Ulster
Unionist leader, David Trimble, said they hoped Mandelson would "
cherry-pick" the recommendations, setting aside the most
controversial suggestions for changing the RUC.
</P>
<P>
Trimble -- now the first minister of the new devolved
government at Stormont -- described the proposals as a "gratuitous
insult" to the memory of the more than 300 RUC officers killed
during the 30 years of the Troubles.
</P>
<P>
The report was broadly welcomed by nationalists but Sinn Fein
said its recommendations did not go far enough towards their aim
of total disbandment of the RUC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
