<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Helps Rehabilitate Rural Roads in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank announced on
Friday that it has approved 103.9 million U.S. dollars in credit
to Vietnam to help rehabilitate rural roads and bridges in 36
provinces into reliable, all-weather roads, giving the rural poor
improved access to markets, health centers and schools.
</P>
<P>
The Rural Transport II Project will concentrate on
rehabilitating rural roads in the poorer sections of Vietnam which
lack basic, all-weather road access. Four additional provinces
will benefit under the same project through a grant of 26.2
million dollars from the British government.
</P>
<P>
In addition to improving the delivery of health care and
education services to the provinces' rural poor, improved road
access is expected to stimulate rural economic activity in the
agriculture and service sectors, which will increase rural incomes
and employment levels in the project area, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The project construction and maintenance activities will
provide additional employment opportunities in rural areas beyond
the project area, the bank added.
</P>
<P>
The credit of 103.9 million dollars will be provided by the
International Development Association, World Bank's concessionary
lending affiliate, at the bank's standard rate for multi-currency
credits with 40 years to maturity and a 10-year grace period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
