<HEADLINE> South Africa to Enter Mercosur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will
become a member of the Southern Common Market (Mercosur),
Brazilian Foreign Minister Luiz Felipe Lampreia said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian foreign minister made the announcement during a
press conference at the Brazilian Trade Confederation.
</P>
<P>
The head of the Brazilian diplomacy said that he has contacted
the South African trade minister to discuss the possible admission
of South Africa into Mercosur since the Brazilian government is
seeking an alternate way after the failure of the negotiations
with the World Trade Organization in Seattle, the United States
</P>
<P>
South Africa is the most important economy of the African
continent, and is a country with which Brazil has big similarity,
said Lampreia.
</P>
<P>
He said that the admission of South Africa into Mercosur could
promote the relations of the Latin American subregional bloc with
the other countries of southern Africa, such as Mozambique, Angola,
and Botswana.
</P>
<P>
He said he will travel to South Africa in February to discuss
the matter.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, created in 1995, is made up of four member countries:
Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay, and Uruguay, and two associated
countries, Chile and Bolivia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
