<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain To Write Off Third World Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Britain is to write off
hundreds of millions of U.S. dollars in debts owed to it by some
of the world's poorest countries, Chancellor of the Exchequer (
Finance Minister) Gordon Brown said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that as a result of the discussions I have been
having that other countries may be prepared to follow," Brown told
BBC Television.
</P>
<P>
"In return for the countries that have debts accepting that
the money that is relieved will not go to military expenditure or
to waste or bureaucracy but go to poverty reduction, we are
prepared on a case by case basis to go up to 100 percent and
therefore relieve all the debts the countries have to the United
Kingdom," he said.
</P>
<P>
Brown said he was preparing to announce debt relief to around
two thirds of the world's 41 poorest nations.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that at least 25 countries will receive help with
their debt burdens during the coming year.
</P>
<P>
In June, The Group of Seven major powers approved their biggest
international debt relief package yet which could write-off about
one third of all the loans owed by the world's poorest countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991218.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Security Council Adopts Resolution on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council narrowly adopted Friday a resolution which could
resume U.N. weapons inspections in Iraq under conditions of
cooperation from Baghdad, but three of the five permanent members
of the council questioned its enforceability with little hope for
Iraq to have the sanctions suspended, if not completely lifted.
</P>
<P>
The resolution passed 11-0, with four abstentions by permanent
council members China, Russia and France, along with Malaysia,
dealing a heavy blow to the attempts by the United States and
Britain to show Iraq a unified stand of the council.
</P>
<P>
The resolution required nine votes and no veto to pass the
council which has been locked in debates for eight months. It sets
up a new arms inspection agency, named the U.N. Monitoring,
Verification and Inspection Commission (UNMOVIC), to replace the U.
N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) charged with dismantling Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM, established in April 3, 1991, has stopped
functioning since the U.S. and Britain launched air strikes at
Iraq a year ago. Baghdad barred it from returning to work,
charging it with serving the U.S. interests.
</P>
<P>
The long and detailed document fell short of spelling out what
exactly Iraq should do before the suspension of the nine-year-old
sanctions imposed after Iraq invaded its neighboring country
Kuwait. Russia, China and France believed that more hope should be
given to the Iraqis in exchange for their cooperation in weapons
inspections.
</P>
<P>
 China's Permanent Representative to the U.N. Qin Huasun told
the council before the voting that at a time of no consensus among
the council members and no commitment from Iraq to cooperation,
the passage of the resolution will not help solve the protracted
issue. He demanded that the new inspection commission be objective,
impartial, transparent, accountable, more sympathetic with the
Iraqis' plight, with its mission clearly defined.
</P>
<P>
Russian Representative Sergey Lavrov stressed that the new
monitoring system must be acceptable by Iraq. "There had been
vague wording in the draft about lifting sanctions, with the
underlying purpose of endlessly postponing the lifting of
sanctions," he said.
</P>
<P>
France decided to abstain from the voting after its efforts
failed to bridge the gaps and secure a consensus among the council
's Big Five. It delayed the voting originally scheduled for last
Friday, fearing its economic interests in Iraq may be hurt if it
went along with the U.S. and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The resolution is intentionally vague on exactly disarmament
tasks Iraq had to take before a suspension of sanctions. It would
suspend the sanctions against Iraq, renewable every 120 days, if
inspectors report that Baghdad had cooperated with them in all
respects and made progress in disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Russia and China wanted the sanctions to be suspended soon
after Iraq allows inspectors to return to work, while the U.S. and
Britain pressed hard for more Iraqi compliance.
</P>
<P>
British Ambassador Jeremy Greenstock, who sponsored the
resolution and presided over the eight-month debate on it, hailed
the vote as an "exceptional achievement" and a show of the council
's unity in seeking a new Iraq policy.
</P>
<P>
U.S. envoy Peter Burleigh told the council, "In adopting this
resolution today, the Security Council has demonstrated that it
has the patience and the resolve to uphold the requirements it set
in resolution 687. Now we await the response from Baghdad."
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM was set up in line with Security Council resolution
687.
</P>
<P>
Reuters reported that leading Iraqi parliamentarian Khalid al-
Douri had rejected the newly adopted U.N. resolution, saying "Iraq
does not accept the new resolution and will not accept any
decision which does not lift the embargo without any restrictions
or conditions."
</P>
<P>
Khalid ak-Douri is leading the parliament's Arab and Foreign
Relations Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
